ois Republicans]]\n[[Category:Illinois Whigs]]\n[[Category:Illinois lawyers]]\n[[Category:Liberalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lincoln family|Abraham]]\n[[Category:Members of the Illinois House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Murdered lawyers]]\n[[Category:People associated with the assassination of Abraham Lincoln]]\n[[Category:People from Coles County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from LaRue County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:People from Macon County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Spencer County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:People of Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People with mood disorders]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Springfield, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Republican Party Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Union political leaders]]\n[[Category:Whig Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n", "name_user": "Gildsons", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_Lincoln"}
{"title_page": "Rape myth", "text_new": "{{About|misconceptions about rape|rape in mythology|List of rape victims from ancient history and mythology}}\n{{Tone|date=November 2017|reason=Unencyclopedic tone in various ways: reads like a brochure, uses informal wording (MOS:WE), and emotive language; making way too many assumptions about gender and age (\"women\") of victims; assumes men are always the perpetrators, presenting \"patriarchy\" arguments in Wikipedia's own voice; etc., etc.  Needs a thorough copyedit.}}\n{{Rape}}\n'''Rape myths''' are [[prejudice|prejudicial]], [[stereotype]]d and false beliefs about [[sexual assault]]s, rapists, and rape victims. They often serve to excuse sexual aggression, create hostility toward victims, and bias criminal prosecution.<ref name=\"Martha Burt\">{{Cite journal |last=Burt |first=Martha R. |title=Cultural myths and supports for rape |journal=[[Journal of Personality and Social Psychology]] |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=217\u2013230 |via=[[PsycINFO|PsycNET]] |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.38.2.217 |pmid=7373511 |date=February 1980}}</ref><ref name=wvu>{{cite web |title=Rape Myths and Facts |author=<!--Staff writers(s); no by-line.--> |date=2012 |url= http://well.wvu.edu/articles/rape_myths_and_facts |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170420122045/http://well.wvu.edu/articles/rape_myths_and_facts |archive-date=20 April 2017 |url-status=dead |work=Well.WVU.edu |publisher=[[West Virginia University]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HSKS\">{{Cite journal |title=Rape Myth Consistency and Gender Differences in Perceiving Rape Victims: A Meta-analysis |author=Hockett, Smith, Klausing, and Saucier |journal=Violence Against Women |date=2016 |volume=22 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013167 |doi=10.1177/1077801215607359 |pmid=26446194 }}</ref>\n\nExtensive research has been conducted about types, acceptance, and impact of rape myths.<ref name=\"RM\">{{cite journal |last1=Lonsway |first1=K. A. |last2=Fitzgerald |first2=L. F. |title=Rape Myths: In Review |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=18 |issue=2 |date=1994 |pages=133\u2013164 |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.1994.tb00448.x}}</ref> Rape myths significantly influence the perspectives of jurors, investigative agencies, judges, perpetrators, and victims.<ref name=\"Temkin\">{{Cite journal |last=Temkin |first=Jennifer |title='And Always Keep A-hold of Nurse, for Fear of Finding Something Worse': Challenging Rape Myths in the Courtroom |url= http://openaccess.city.ac.uk/2527/1/NCLR1304_05.pdf|journal=New Criminal Law Review |volume=13 |issue=4 |page=710  |doi=10.1525/nclr.2010.13.4.710 |year=2010}}</ref> False views about rape lead to [[victim blaming]], shaming, questioning of the victim's honesty, and other problems. Determination of the guilt of the accused, and sentencing for sexual crimes, are also influenced by these beliefs.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Discretion, Discrimination and the Rule of Law |last=Satish |first=Mrinal |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |date=2016 |isbn= |pages=}}</ref>{{page needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Development of the concept==\nRape myths originate from various cultural stereotypes, such as traditional [[gender role]]s, acceptance of interpersonal violence, and misunderstanding the nature of sexual assault.<ref name=\"Martha Burt\" /> [[Matthew Hale (jurist)|Matthew Hale]], a British jurist in the 17<sup>th</sup> century, suggests that rape is \u201can accusation easily to be made and hard to be proved and harder to be defended against by the party accused, tho [''sic''] never so innocent\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=Dawn Rae|title=Rape in Chicago: Race, Myth and the Courts|publisher=University of Illinois Press|year=2012|isbn=|location=Urbana|pages=1}}</ref> His historical thoughts invisibly support many rape myths we see today, and continue to be reproduced in rape trials.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nRape myths first became a topic of research during the 1970s, when a number of studies and books explored the concept.<ref name=\"Brownmiller1975\">{{cite book|author=Susan Brownmiller|title=Against Our Will: Men, Women, and Rape|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qXhzjM8b_VUC|year=1975|publisher=Fawcett Columbine|isbn=978-0-449-90820-4}}</ref><ref>HS Feild, \"Attitudes toward rape: A Comparative Analysis of Police, Rapists, Crisis Counselors, and Citizens,\" ''Journal of Personality and Social Psychology,'' 36 (2), 1978: 166- 179.</ref><ref name=\"Schwen\">{{cite journal |last1=Schwendinger |first1=Julia R. |last2=Schwendinger |first2=Herman |date=1974 |title=Rape Myths: In Legal, Theoretical, and Everyday Practice |url= |journal=Crime and Social Justice |volume=1 |issue= |pages=18\u201326 |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> In 1974, for example, feminist writer [[Susan Brownmiller]] decried \"male myths of rape\" which \"deliberately obscure the true nature of rape\" in her book ''[[Against Our Will|Against Our Will: Men, Women and Rape]]''.<ref name=\"Brownmiller1975\"/> The same year, criminologists Julia and Herman Schwendinger studied common misconceptions about rape, including the notion that rape was impossible - i.e., that any woman who really wanted to could prevent a rape - the idea victims of rape were \"asking for it,\" and the idea that men rape because of \"uncontrollable passions.\" They termed these misconceptions \"sexist myths\" which \"influence the treatment of women victims.\"<ref name=\"Schwen\"/> Both Brownmiller's work and the Schwendingers' study suggested that rape myths perpetuated male violence against women by placing blame on the victim, excusing the rapist, and minimizing or justifying the act of rape.<ref name=\"irma1999\"/>\n\nIn 1980, Martha Burt published the first major study of rape myth acceptance.<ref name=\"irma1999\"/> Burt defined rape myths as \"prejudicial, stereotyped and false beliefs about rape, rape victims and rapists\" which create \"a climate hostile to rape victims.\"<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/> Burt's definition has been widely used.<ref name=\"Bohner\">{{cite book |last1=Bohner |first1=Gerd |last2=Eyssel|first2=Friederike|last3=Pina|first3=Afroditi|last4=Viki|first4=Tendayi|last5=Siebler|first5=Frank|editor1-last=Horvath|editor1-first=Miranda A.H.|editor2-last=Brown|editor2-first=Jennifer M.|date=2013 |title=Rape: Challenging Contemporary Thinking |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=SpkzxXmtI50C&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= |publisher=Willan (Routledge)|pages=17\u201345 |isbn=978-1134026463}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Kimberly A. Lonsway and Louise F. Fitzgerald defined rape myths as \"attitudes and beliefs that are generally false but are widely and persistently held, and that serve to deny and justify male sexual aggression against women.\"<ref>Kimberly A. Lonsway, Louise F. Fitzgerald, \"Rape Myths: In Review\" ''Psychology of Women Quarterly'' 18 (2), June 1994: 133-164.</ref>\n\nSome scholars, such as [[Gerd Bohner]]  and Heike Gerger, have argued that descriptors such as \"false\" and \"widely held\" should not be included in a formal definition of what rape myths are since myths are often constructed in a way that are impossible to falsify, (as in the example, \"many women ''secretly'' desire to be raped,\" where \"secret\" desire cannot be disproven) and the degree to which rape myths are \"widely held\" or accepted may vary over time.<ref name=\"Bohner\"/> Bohner has offered an alternative definition of rape myths as \"descriptive or prescriptive beliefs about rape (ie, about its causes, context, consequences, perpetrators, victims and their interaction) that serve to deny, downplay or justify sexual violence against women.\"<ref>Gerd Bohner, ''Vergewaltigungsmythen'' (Rape Myths) Verlag Empirische P\u00e4dagogik, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"Bohner\"/>\n\nWhile scholars disagree somewhat on how to precisely define the concept of rape myths, and rape myths can vary across different cultures and societies, there is a general consensus that there are four basic types of rape myths: those that blame the victim for their rape, those that express doubt or disbelief about victim's reports of a rape, those that exonerate the rapist, and those that suggest that only a certain type of woman gets raped.<ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref>Grubb, Amy & Turner, Emily. (2012). \"Attribution of blame in rape cases: A review of the impact of rape myth acceptance, gender role conformity and substance use on victim blaming\" ''Aggression and Violent Behavior'' 17 (5) 443-452.\n*\"Rape myths vary among societies and cultures. However, they consistently follow a pattern whereby, they blame the victim for their rape, express a disbelief in claims of rape, exonerate the perpetrator and allude that only certain types of women are raped.\"</ref>\n\nLonsway, Fitzgerald and Diana L. Payne wrote in 1999 that the term \"rape myth\" does not imply that a given scenario ''never'' occurs, and \"it is clear that any individual instance might conform to the characteristics described in cultural male mythology,\" since there is \"undeniably some percentage of women\" who have made false reports of rape, and there are \"certain situational or personal characteristics that differentiate women who have been raped from those who have not.\" They argue, however, that rape myths are \"generally false\" in nature, and function to deny and justify the victimization of women.<ref name=\"irma1999\">{{cite journal |title=Rape Myth Acceptance: Exploration of Its Structure and Its Measurement Using the ''Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale'' |first1=Diana L. |last1=Payne |first2=Kimberly A. |last2=Lonsway |first3=Louise F. |last3=Fitzgerald |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |volume= 33 |issue=1 |date=March 1999 |pages=27\u201368 |doi=10.1006/jrpe.1998.2238|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0815388f3263ea1b4eaf7facb5e23defdb80bbcc }}</ref> \n\n=== Heteronormative discourses ===\n[[Heteronormativity]] and associated discourses undergird and perpetuate many rape myths. The construction of the male sexual subject and female passive object serves to de-legitimatize allegations of sexual assault that are contrary to heterosexual norms, such as where women are perpetrators and men are victims. Through the \u201cmale sexual drive discourse\u201d, it is thought that men are always ready and desiring sex, and women \u201cactivate their interest\u201d,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gavey|first=Nicola|title=Just sex? The cultural scaffolding of rape|publisher=Routledge|year=2019|isbn=|edition=Second|location=Abingdon, Oxon|pages=99}}</ref> which can invalidate experiences that do not confirm to this discourse. Similarly, the \u201chave/hold discourse\u201d produces women as asexual, and heterosexual pleasure comes secondary to the ultimate goal of having a relationship and family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gavey|first=|title=Just sex|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100}}</ref>\n\n==Common rape myths==\nCommon rape myths may include:\n*That women commonly or routinely lie about rape.<ref name=\"EMH\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Mental Health|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5aLxBQAAQBAJ&pg=RA3-PA15|date=26 August 2015|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-12-397753-3|pages=3}}\n*\"Common rape myths may include: women often lie about rape, a victim's clothing can precipitate a sexual assault, rape is the fault of the victim if she was intoxicated, and when a male pays for a date, the woman is expected to reciprocate with sexual intercourse.\"</ref><ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\">{{cite book|author1=Paula K. Lundberg-Love|author2=Shelly L. Marmion|title=\"Intimate\" Violence Against Women: When Spouses, Partners, Or Lovers Attack|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=OnEq_IbDSUQC&lpg=PA59&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98967-5|pages=59\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\">{{cite book|author1=Holly Johnson|author2=Bonnie S. Fisher|author3=Veronique Jaquier|title=Critical Issues on Violence Against Women: International Perspectives and Promising Strategies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pD62BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA96|date=5 December 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-00603-7|pages=96\u2013}}\n*\"Some rape myths include: that women fantasize about being raped; that women routinely lie about rape; that men cannot rape their intimate partners; that rape is simply unwanted sex and not a violent crime; and that victims are usually attacked by strangers.\"</ref><ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref name=Hayes>Rebecca M. Hayes1, Katherine Lorenz2, Kristin A. Bell, \"Victim Blaming Others: Rape Myth Acceptance and the Just World Belief,\" ''Feminist Criminology'' 8 (3), April 2013: 202-220.\n*\"Common rape myths include: the misconception that the victim\u2019s clothing precipitated the assault, that women often lie about rape, that rape is the victim\u2019s fault if they were intoxicated at the time of the assault, and; when a male pays for a date, the woman is expected to reciprocate with sexual intercourse.</ref><ref name=\"irma1999\"/><ref name=Rich>{{cite book|author=Karen Rich|title=Interviewing Rape Victims: Practice and Policy Issues in an International Context|date=2014|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|isbn=9781137353221}}\n*\"Rape Myths include, but are not limited to, each of the following statements or beliefs: Rape is rare, Rape is not harmful, Most victims lie about rape, Some victims deserve to be raped, Women drive men to rape them by wearing provocative attire, Rape is a crime of passion, Rapists are mentally retarded/seriously mentally ill... Only certain kinds of women are raped, A man cannot 'rape' his wife, Some women secretly want to be raped.\"</ref><ref name=Reddington/>\n*That what the victim is wearing can lead to a sexual assault, or that rape is the victim's fault if they wore revealing clothes.<ref name=\"EMH\"/><ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref name=Hayes/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref>Moor, Avigail (2010). She Dresses to Attract, He Perceives Seduction: A Gender Gap in Attribution of Intent to Women\u2019s Revealing Style of Dress and its Relation to Blaming the Victims of Sexual Violence. Journal of International Women's Studies, 11(4), 115-127.</ref><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=ymrk2002/><ref name=Rich/>\n*That victims bear responsibility for an assault if they were intoxicated when it happened.<ref name=\"EMH\"/><ref>Hayes, R. M., Lorenz, K., & Bell, K. A. (2013). Victim blaming others: Rape myth acceptance and the just world belief. Feminist Criminology, 1557085113484788.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |first1=Vanessa |last1=Munro |first2=Emily |last2=Finch |date= |title=Juror Stereotypes and Blame Attribution in Rape Cases Involving Intoxicants |url= |journal=British Journal of Criminology |volume=25|issue=1|pages=25\u201338 }}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants=R v. Malone |reporter=2 Cr. App. R. |volume=447 |date=1998|url=http://ww3.lawschool.cornell.edu/AvonResources/R-v-Malone.pdf}}</ref>\n*That most rapes are committed by strangers.<ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"doi.org\">Ben-David, S. & Schneider, O. Sex Roles (2005) 53: 385. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11199-005-6761-4</ref> (In reality, most rapes are committed by friends, family, or other individuals known to the victim.)<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://ncrb.nic.in/StatPublications/CII/CII2015/FILES/Compendium-15.11.16.pdf |title=Crime in India 2015 Compendium |last= |first= |date= |work=NCRB.NIC.in |publisher=National Crime Records Bureau, India |access-date=March 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Temkin\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ellison |first=Louis |title=Reacting to Rape: Exploring Mock Jurors' Assessments of Complainant Credibility |url= |journal=The British Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=2 |page=202 |doi=10.1093/bjc/azn077 |year=2008}}</ref><ref name=Reddington/>\n*That when a male pays for a dinner or date, a woman is expected to reciprocate with intercourse.<ref name=\"EMH\"/><ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=Hayes/>\n*That women who are raped often deserve it - particularly if they entered a man's home or got in his car, or that such actions indicate consent to sex.<ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=Rich/>\n*That it is not rape unless the victim fights/physically resists, or that it is not rape unless the victim is physically coerced or injured.<ref name=\"Kennedy 2012 309\u2013311\">{{cite journal |last=Kennedy |first=K. M. |title=The relationship of victim injury to the progression of sexual crimes through the criminal justice system |journal=Journal of Forensic and Legal Medicine |date=2012 |volume=19 |issue=6 |pages=309\u2013311 |doi=10.1016/j.jflm.2012.04.033|pmid=22847045 |hdl=10379/12225 |url=https://www.lenus.ie/bitstream/10147/266322/1/RelationshipofVictim.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=ymrk2002>Yancey-Martin, Reynolds, Keith,\"Gender Bias and Feminist Consciousness among Judges and Attorneys: A Standpoint Theory Analysis\", 2002, {{doi|10.1086/337941}}</ref> (In reality, many rapes do not involve physical coercion, as in cases where the victim is impaired/unconscious, or where an unequal power relationship forces the victim to submit.)<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.lawctopus.com/academike/section-375-analysis-of-provisions-relating-to-rape/ |first=Soumya Singh |last=Chauhan |title=Section 375: Analysis of Provisions Relating to Rape |date=14 February 2015 |work=Academike |publisher=Lawctopus |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite court |url= https://indiankanoon.org/doc/1607781/ |litigants=Rao Harnarain Singh, Sheoji Singh, et al. v. The State |date=12 August 1957 |court=Punjab-Haryana High Court, India |reporter=AIR 1958 P H 123; 1958 CriLJ 563. |via=IndianKanoon.org |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Evaluating Stranger and Acquaintance Rape: The Role of Benevolent Sexism in Perpetrator Blame and Recommended Sentence Length |url= |journal=Law and Human Behavior |volume=28|issue= 3|pages= 295\u2013303|doi= 10.1023/B:LAHU.0000029140.72880.69|pmid= 15264448|year= 2004|last1= Viki|first1= G. Tendayi|last2= Abrams|first2= Dominic|last3= Masser|first3= Barbara}}</ref><ref name=\"Kennedy 2012 309\u2013311\"/>\n*That a woman should be able to avoid rape by \"fighting off\" the rapist, and that she has the responsibility to do so.<ref name=\"Temkin\" /><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/>\n*That some women secretly want to be raped.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=Rich/><ref name=Reddington/><ref name=\"Edwards 761\u2013773\">{{Cite journal|last=Edwards|first=Katie M.|last2=Turchik|first2=Jessica A.|last3=Dardis|first3=Christina M.|last4=Reynolds|first4=Nicole|last5=Gidycz|first5=Christine A.|date=December 2011|title=Rape Myths: History, Individual and Institutional-Level Presence, and Implications for Change|journal=Sex Roles|volume=65|issue=11\u201312|pages=761\u2013773|doi=10.1007/s11199-011-9943-2|issn=0360-0025}}</ref>\n*That it is impossible to rape one's wife or intimate partner.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=Rich/>\n*That rape is simply unwanted sex, not a violent crime.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/>\n*That women \"ask for\" rape - for example, by flirting, dressing provocatively, consuming alcohol or behaving promiscuously<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/> - or that only certain \"kinds of\" women (i.e., \"bad girls\") are raped.<ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=\"irma1999\"/><ref name=\"McMahon\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=McMahon |author-first1=Sarah|author-last2=Farmer|author-first2=G. Lawrence |date=June 2011 |title=An Updated Measure for Assessing Subtle Rape Myths |url= |journal=Social Work Research |volume=35|issue=2|pages=71\u201381  |doi=10.1093/swr/35.2.71}}</ref><ref name=Rich/><ref name=Reddington/>\n*That men are unable to control themselves once they become sexually excited, that women are responsible for rape if they allow things to go too far,<ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=ymrk2002/> or that consent to kissing, petting, etc. constitutes consent to intercourse.<ref name=\"Cocker\">{{Cite journal |last=Cocker |first=Ann |date=2005 |title=PTSD Symptoms Among Men and Women Survivors of Intimate Partner Violence: The Role of Risk and Protective Factors |url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1c3864218194aa24347e67761cb3115b0cf9973e|journal=Violence & Victims |volume=20 |issue=6 |page=625 |doi=10.1891/0886-6708.20.6.625 }}</ref>\n*That women commonly falsely allege rape out of spite, to overcome guilt after a sexual encounter they regret, to cover up an unwanted pregnancy, or for attention.<ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=ymrk2002/>\n*That rape must be sexually motivated. Many researchers have concluded that power and/or anger, not sex, are often the dominant motivator of rapes.<ref name=\"doi.org\"/><ref name=aiws>{{cite journal |url= https://uiowa.edu/crisp/sites/uiowa.edu.crisp/files/6.8.pdf |title=Perceived Motivation for Rape: Gender Differences in Beliefs About Female and Male Rape |first1=Irina |last1=Anderson |first2=Victoria |last2=Swainson |journal=Current Research in Social Psychology |volume=6 |issue=8 |date=17 April 2001 |publisher=[[University of Iowa]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n*That most rapists are psychotic or mentally ill.<ref name=aiws>{{cite journal |url= https://uiowa.edu/crisp/sites/uiowa.edu.crisp/files/6.8.pdf |title=Perceived Motivation for Rape: Gender Differences in Beliefs About Female and Male Rape |first1=Irina |last1=Anderson |first2=Victoria |last2=Swainson |journal=Current Research in Social Psychology |volume=6 |issue=8 |date=17 April 2001 |publisher=[[University of Iowa]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=Rich/><ref name=Reddington>{{cite book|title=Sexual Assault: The Victims, the Perpetrators, and the Criminal Justice System|author1-last=Reddington|author1-first=Frances P.|author2-last=Kreisel|author2-first=Betsy Wright|publisher=Carolina Academic Press|date=2009|isbn=9781594605772}}</ref>\n*That consent to one sexual encounter constitutes consent to another (i.e., that it cannot be rape if the victim and rapist have previously had consensual sex).<ref name=\"Cocker\" />\n*That \"real\" victims report rape immediately. (In reality, victims often don't report rapes immediately due to societal pressure, possible backlash, and trauma such as rape related [[post traumatic stress disorder]], also known as [[rape trauma syndrome]]. Victims of rape may also feel feelings of guilt and shame which deter them from reporting the crime, or doing so promptly.)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Neil Kibble|title=Case Comments: R v. Doody [2009]|journal=Criminal Law Review|volume=2009|date=2009|pages=590\u2013597}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Chennels |first=Rebecca |date= |title=Sentencing: The 'real rape' myth |url= |journal=Agenda: Empowering Women for Gender Equity |volume=82 |page=23 }}</ref><ref name=\"HSKS\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://in.reuters.com/article/india-delhi-gang-rape-women-safety-polic/analysis-how-indias-police-and-judiciary-fail-rape-victims-idINDEE90F0AY20130116 |title=Analysis: How India's police and judiciary fail rape victims |last=Bhalla |first=Nita |work=In.Reuters.com |publisher=[[Reuters]] |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/182369.pdf |title=The Sexual Victimization of College Women |last1=Fisher |first1=Bonnie S. |last2=Cullen |first2=Francis T. |last3=Turner |first3=Michael G. |date=December 2000 |location=Washington DC |publisher=[[National Institute of Justice]] / [[Bureau of Justice Statistics]] |via=NCJRS.gov ([[National Criminal Justice Reference Service]]) |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://globalnews.ca/news/1845136/why-dont-women-report-rape-because-most-get-no-justice-when-they-do/ |title=Why don't women report rape? Because most get no justice when they do |work=Global News |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rape myths involving male victims===\nMost of the rape myths listed above deal with the rape of women by men. There has been less research on perceptions of rapes of male victims, whether by women or by other men. The following have been identified:<ref name=COR>Kristine M. Chapleau, Debra L. Oswald, Brenda L. Russell, \"Male Rape Myths: The Role of Gender, Violence, and Sexism\", Journal of Interpersonal Violence, Volume: 23 issue: 5, page(s): 600-615, {{doi|10.1177/0886260507313529}}</ref> Rape myths can stem from the media and are largely held by the general population. Research suggests that a common myth is that men experience little trauma when perpetrated by a woman.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hammond |first1=Laura |last2=Loannou |first2=Maria |last3=Fewster |first3=Martha |title=Perception of male rape and sexual assault in a male sample from the United Kingdom: Barriers to reporting and the impacts of victimization |journal=Journal of Investigative Psychology and Offender Profiling |volume=14 |issue=2 |pages=133\u2013149 |date=June 1, 2017 |doi=10.1002/jip.1462 |url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/29241/7/Perceptions%20of%20Male%20Rape%20and%20Sexual%20Assault.pdf }}</ref>\n\n*That being raped by a male attacker is synonymous with the loss of masculinity.\n*That men who are sexually assaulted by men must be gay.\n*That men are incapable of functioning sexually unless they are sexually aroused.\n*That men cannot be forced to have sex against their will.\n*That men are less affected by sexual assault than women.\n*That men are in a constant state of readiness to accept any sexual opportunity.\n*That a man is expected to be able to defend himself against sexual assault.\nThey may also include the following beliefs:<ref name=SJSJ>{{cite journal | last1 = Struckman-Johnson | first1 = C. | last2 = Struckman-Johnson | first2 = D. | year = 1992 | title = Acceptance of male rape myths among college men and women | url = | journal = Sex Roles | volume = 27 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 85\u2013100 | doi=10.1007/bf00290011}}</ref><ref name=COR/><ref name=\"Edwards 761\u2013773\"/>\n\n*\"Denial\": That male rape does not exist.  \n*\"Blame\": That male rape is victim's fault.\n*\"Trauma\": That men are less traumatized by the rape.\n\nThe latter two categories show higher myth acceptance in the case when the perpetrator is a female.<ref name=SJSJ/><ref name=COR/> Male victims are also placed with the blame of their rape more often than female victims.<ref name=\"Turchik 211\u2013226\">{{Cite journal|last=Turchik|first=Jessica A.|last2=Edwards|first2=Katie M.|date=April 2012|title=Myths about male rape: A literature review.|journal=Psychology of Men & Masculinity|volume=13|issue=2|pages=211\u2013226|doi=10.1037/a0023207|issn=1939-151X}}</ref>\n\n=== Rape Myths and Disabilities ===\n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Benedet |first1=Janine |last2=Grant |first2=Isabel |title=Sexual Assault and the Meaning of Power and Authority for Women with Mental Disabilities |journal=Springer Science+Business Media Dordrecht 2014 |date=4 July 2014 |pages=131-154}}</ref>\nWhile disabled people are viewed as asexual, they are also hypersexualized which can encourage sexual abuse.  Disabled people are desexualized and hypersexualized at the same time which they both work against the person. People living with disabilities are viewed on a binary scale as they are seen as all or nothing. If they are seen as capable, they are always seen as capable and if you are seen as incapable they are always denied sex. Therefore the law needs to think in a situational way as people with disabilities have different levels of capabilities, \u201cLegally, it may cause us to miss the multifaceted ways in which people with mental disabilities resist or object to sexual assault and also to assume that compliance represents consent rather than acquiescence in the face of coercion or exploitative inducements\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Benedet |first1=Janine |last2=Grant |first2=Isabel |title=Sexual Assault and the Meaning of Power and Authority for Women with Mental Disabilities |journal=Springer Science+Business Media Dordrecht 2014 |date=4 July 2014 |pages=131-154}}</ref>. The view that they are asexual or hypersexual creates the idea that they cannot be victims of sexual violence, labeling them as an unrapable group. This myth is further articulated within the Benedet and Grant article, they discuss a prominent rape myth that labels people of disabilities to be \u201clucky\u201d to get any male attention, including coerced and nonconsensual sex. Any sex, however coercive, is construed as better than no sex which was illustrated by Chenoweth\n\n=== Transgender Rape Myths ===\nAs trans-gender people challenge dominant gender norms, this often leaves them in a place of marginalization. Transgender people are the most likely to face violence and backlash as people perceive them as inherently deceptive as they are said to be concealing their \u201ctrue sex\u201d. This is a very transphobic assumption that rationalizes the violence against trans people (mainly trans women) and the criminalization of trans people (mainly trans men). \n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schilt |first1=Kristen |last2=Westbrook |first2=Lauren |title=DOING GENDER, DOING HETERONORMATIVITY |journal=GENDER & SOCIETY |date=August 4, 2009 |volume=23 |pages=440-464}}</ref>\n\n\u201cPenis Panic\u201d emerges in the discourse surrounding gender-neutral washrooms, due to the belief that men (and their penis) have a \u201cpropensity to rape\u201d <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Westbrook|first=Laurel|last2=Schilt|first2=Kristen|date=2014|title=Doing gender, determining gender: Transgender people, gender panics, and the maintenance of the sex/gender/sexuality system|url=|journal=Gender and Society|volume=Vol 28, No. 1|pages=32 - 57|via=}}</ref>. Therefore transgender women are portrayed, due to their penis, as a threat to women if they share the same washroom. Susan Brownmiller explores the biological determinism that defines rape due to the structural differences in men versus women <ref>{{Cite book|last=Cahill|first=Ann|title=Rethinking Rape|publisher=Cornell University Press|year=2001|isbn=|location=Ithaca|pages=21}}</ref> This myth is furthered by the idea that allowing transgender people to use the restroom that aligns with their perceived gender will end up allowing male sexual predators into women\u2019s bathrooms. \n\nAnother common myth is the belief that no one wants to sexually assault a transgender person due to their identity. But that is not true, as transgender folks tend to be more vulnerable they could be more at risk to face sexual violence, especially as a form of hate crime. A common misconception is that sexual assault is primarily about sexual attraction, but rather it is about the dynamics of power and control over another person.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foundation |first1=LGBT |title=A guide for trans people who have been affected by sexual violence |url=https://www.gendergp.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Guide-for-trans-people-affected-by-sexual-violence-1.pdf |website=lgbt.foundation/counselling |publisher=LGBT Foundation |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Rape Myths in the Prison System ===\nActions such as strip searches, body-cavity searches, and non-consensual medical interventions within the prison system are not violent acts is a common myth. Looking at similar actions occurring outside the prison shows nothing less than sexual assault as these acts lack consent, often have present resistance, and can have traumatizing effects <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref>. And like many acts of sexual violence, these types of searches are also a form of exerting control over another individual.\n\nIt is believed that some prisoners have brought sexual abuse on themselves or deserve the violence they face through the crime they committed that landed them in prison, i.e. sex offenders or child molesters<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ferranti |first1=Seth |title=Why Are So Many Sex Offenders Getting Murdered in California's Prisons? |url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/ppmjy8/why-sex-offenders-are-getting-slaughtered-in-california-prisons-218 |website=VICE |publisher=VICE |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>. But that is not true, no one deserves to be a victim of sexual violence. The prison systems have normalized sexual violence through staff interactions (abuse of power, strip searches, body cavity searches, and other nonconsensual acts), as well as ignored the violence occurring between the inmates <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref> <ref>{{cite web |last1=Wakefield |first1=Jonny |title=Alberta prisoners made 67 allegations of sexual assault in the last five fiscal years; Only one resulted in a criminal charge |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/insight/violent-and-coercive-sexual-assault-behind-bars-is-a-taboo-topic-but-statistics-tell-only-part-of-the-story/ |website=Edmonton Journal |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>. The normalization of sexual violence within prisons allows the system and power dynamics to be upheld. In situations where sexual violence becomes normalized, it desensitizes people to the issue, creating the belief that prisoners will come out more criminal. The negative effects to the normalization of sexual violence in prisons do not stop there, it allows many allegations to go unnoticed, leaving many victims without prosecution and the issue to not be viewed as a systemic problem <ref>{{cite web |last1=Wakefield |first1=Jonny |title=Alberta prisoners made 67 allegations of sexual assault in the last five fiscal years; Only one resulted in a criminal charge |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/insight/violent-and-coercive-sexual-assault-behind-bars-is-a-taboo-topic-but-statistics-tell-only-part-of-the-story/ |website=Edmonton Journal |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>..  \n\nThe Prison Rape Elimination Act (PREA) helps to ensure prisoner's safety against sexual violence by, \u201climiting circumstances where prisoners experience touching, viewing, or other manipulation of their genitals, anus, buttocks, or breasts against their will\u201d <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref>.  Although this is not the case, as it rather punishes consensual interactions amongst the prisoners, resulting in the deeper issue of homophobia. Or it goes in the other direction of reducing sexual assault into consensual acts. PREA leaves many non-consensual acts virtually unregulated which go against its intended purpose.\n\nThe evil perpetrator / innocent victim dyad commonly found within the prison systems idea of sexual assault reduces violence to an individual act that occurs between two people. The prison systems, however, creates sexual violence as a \u201cgroup-based phenomenon that does group-based harm\u201d, which typically results in the reinforcement of hierarchies, fear amongst certain groups, and this belief that not all people deserve to have control over their bodies <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref>.\n\n=== Racial rape myths ===\nScholars have argued that [[racism]] remains a critical component of sexual violence discourse within the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arkles|first=Gabriel|date=2015|title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence|url=|journal=Northeastern University Law Journal|volume=Vol. 7, No. 1|pages=71 - 130|via=}}</ref> Alcoff and Gray state that white victims who report they were raped by non-white perpetrators are more likely to be believed than non-white victims who report white perpetrators.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alcoff|first=Linda|last2=Gray|first2=Laura|date=Winter 1993|title=Survivor Discourse: Transgression or Recuperation?|url=|journal=Signs|volume=Vol 18, No. 2|pages=260 - 290|via=}}</ref> Not only are non-white bodies seen as not rapable, but non-white men are seen as sexually deviant, violent, and dangerous. In the context of African American men, Dawn Rae Flood argues that the history of race relations within America constructs accused African American men as guilty of any accusations against a white woman, because of their \u201cinherently criminal sexual nature\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFlood argues that under [[white supremacy]], black sexuality was constructed as \u201cforeign\u201d, \u201csavage\u201d, immoral, and predatory towards white women.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=4}}</ref> Rooted in slavery and the white slave owners\u2019 access to Black women, the \u201cJezebel\u201d rape myth portrays Black women as \u201cunrapable\u201d,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=12}}</ref> due to a belief that they are \u201csexually promiscuous\u201d and would not refuse to consent.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=77}}</ref> Black women are also portrayed as asexual, due to the \u201cmammy\u201d stereotype, which depicts them as motherly and lacking sexual characteristics.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=81}}</ref>\n\nSherene Razack argues that indigenous people are seen as hypersexual, and she argues that \u201cbodies in degenerate spaces\u201d lose their personhood due to the naturalization of violence, and in the context of indigenous sex workers, these women through being marked \u201cas a body to be violated\", become \u201cunrapable\u201d.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Razack|first=Sherene|date=2000|title=Gendered Racial Violence and Spatialized Justice: The Murder Pamela George|url=|journal=Canadian Journal of Law and Society|volume=Vol 15, No. 2|pages=91 - 130|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Marital rape myths ===\nJennifer Koshan states that many marital rape myths were born from British attitudes and laws during colonial times and were rationales that granted criminal immunity to husbands accused of marital rape.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=Jennifer|title=The Criminalisation of Marital Rape and Law Reform in Canada: A Modest Feminist Success Story in Combatting Marital Rape Myths in The Right to Say No: Marital Rape and Law Reform in Canada, Ghana, Kenya and Malawi|publisher=Hart Publishing|year=2017|isbn=|editor-last=Randall|editor-first=Melanie|location=Portland, Oregon|pages=144|editor-last2=Koshan|editor-first2=Jennifer|editor-last3=Nyaundi|editor-first3=Patricia}}</ref> Such myths include:\n\n* Women in intimate relationships are in a state of perpetual consent,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/marital-rape-myths-have-no-place-in-canadian-law/article36749822/|title=Marital rape myths have no place in Canadian law|last=Koshan|first=Jennifer|last2=Randall|first2=Melanie|date=2017|website=The Globe and Mail|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last3=Sheehy|first3=Elizabeth}}</ref> or the \u201cimplied consent theory\u201d.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=|title=The Criminalisation of Martial Rape|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=145}}</ref>\n* Wives could not be raped, because they joined \u201cthe person of her husband\u201d, or the \u201ctheory of coverture\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Wives became the property of their husband, and could be raped without regard for punishment.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Women that consent to sex with their partner after being raped cannot claim to being raped.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Being raped by one\u2019s husband is \u201cless severe than being raped by a stranger.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=Jennifer|url=http://theequalityeffect.org/pdfs/maritalrapecanadexperience.pdf|title=The Legal Treatment of Marital Rape and Women\u2019s Equality: An Analysis of the Canadian Experience|publisher=The Equality Effect|year=2010|isbn=|location=Toronto|pages=50}}</ref>\n* Marital rape allegations are \u201cvengeful women crying rape\u201d,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Busby|first=Karen|date=2012|title=Every Breath You Take: Erotic Asphyxiation, Vengeful Wives, and Other Enduring Myths in Spousal Sexual Assault Prosecutions|url=|journal=Canadian Journal of Women and the Law|volume=Vol 24, Issue 2|pages=328 - 358|via=}}</ref> and women are \u201cprone to fabrication\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=|title=The Legal Treatment|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=57}}</ref>\n\n\n==Problems arising out of rape myths==\n\nThe prevalence of rape myths is a major reason for rape [[victim blaming]] and [[Social stigma|stigmatization]].<ref name=\"wvu\" /><ref name=\"HSKS\" /> Rape myths can cause victims of rape to blame themselves for their rape, or to not report their assault, and they can also shape the responses of judges and juries, causing a negative impact on rape victims.<ref name=Rich/> Some studies have shown that police officers are often distrustful of rape victims' account of their victimization, and that many of them believe some common rape myths.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=Jordan>{{cite journal|author-last=Jordan|author-first=Jan|date=February 2004|title=Beyond Belief? Police, Rape, and Women's Credibility|journal=Criminology and Criminal Justice|volume=4|issue=1|pages=29\u201359|doi=10.1177/1466802504042222|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/291e2b1d81cc8afe17eaa2a95a62f631dde58823}}</ref><ref name=Page>{{cite journal|author-last=Page|author-first=Amy Dellinger|title=Gateway to Reform? Policy Implications of Police Officers' Attitudes Toward Rape|journal=American Journal of Criminal Justice|volume=33|issue=1|date=2008|pages=44\u201358|doi=10.1007/s12103-007-9024-9}}</ref> Also, many who believe even one rape myth typically also do not believe female rape myths any more or any less than male rape myths.<ref name=\"Turchik 211\u2013226\"/> Though, men are also more likely to warrant rape myths rather than women.<ref name=\"Edwards 761\u2013773\"/>\n\nDue to reported higher rape myth acceptance among males than females, as well as because of other gender-based differences in perceptions and standpoints, one analysis by Patricia Yancey Martin, John R. Reynolds and Shelley Keith suggested that \"a judiciary made up solely of men differs from one made up of more equal proportions of women and men\".<ref name=\"ymrk2002\" /><ref>{{cite book |first=Martha |last=Reeves |title=Women in Business: Theory and Cases |edition=2nd |date=2016 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=NqnZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT70 |page=70 |via=Google Books |access-date=7 November 2017|isbn=9781317363316 }}</ref> This commentary is furthered by the writings of Mallios and Meisner, who state that rape myth acceptance is problematic in judicial settings. They assert that ''[[voir dire]]'' can be used to curb jury bias related to preconceived notions regarding rape.<ref>Mallios C, Meisner T. Educating juries in sexual assault cases: Using voir dire to eliminate jury bias. Strategies: The Prosecutors\u2019 Newsletter on Violence Against Women, 2010; 2. http://www.aequitasresource.org/EducatingJuriesInSexualAssaultCasesPart1.pdf</ref> This problem is further heightened by the fact that investigative agencies, various participants in the Legal System, and points of contacts for rape victims, for example the nearest doctor, are likelier to be male, than female. The 2015 book ''Asking for It''&nbsp;by [[Kate Harding]] talks about common rape myths and about the differences between male and female rapes. One in five women and one in seventy-one men in the United States will find out what it's like to be raped, according to Harding. She writes, \"Women are no more important than any other potential victims, but we are the primary targets of the messages and myths that sustain rape culture. Anyone can be raped, but men aren't conditioned to live in terror of it, nor are they constantly warned that their clothing, travel choices, alcohol consumption, and expressions of sexuality are likely to bring violations upon them.\"<ref name=\"Harding\">{{Cite book |title=Asking for It |last=Harding |first=Kate |publisher=Da Capo Press |date=2015 |isbn=978-0-7382-1702-4 |location=Philadelphia |pages=}}</ref>{{rp|19}}\n\nSuch stereotypes reduce the inclination of victims to report instances of rape, harassment, and assault. This reduced reporting of crimes might present a rosy picture and would further the problem, by leading to beliefs that these crimes that are reported are fake, false, or unlikely to be true.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn ''Asking for It'', Harding writes of rape that \"we tend not to treat it as a serious crime unless there's simultaneously evidence of another one\".<ref name=\"Harding\"/>{{rp|11}}  The author also quotes psychologist [[David Lisak]]. He says that \"Ultimately, only a tiny handful of rapists ever serve time for rape, a shocking outcome given that we view rape as close kin to murder in the taxonomy of violent crime\".<ref name=\"Harding\"/>{{rp|11}}\n\n=== Twin myths ===\nThe ''twin myths'' suggest that a victim\u2019s previous sexual history i) makes them less believable, and/or ii) more likely to consent. Canadian law does allow for the inclusion of previous sexual history, but defence counsel must present a s.276 application and a hearing is held to ensure the evidence will not be used in the context of the twin myths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://certificate.queenslaw.ca/blog/the-supreme-court-sexual-assault-and-twin-myths|title=The Supreme Court, Sexual Assault and \"Twin Myths\"|last=Rawson|first=Kate|date=2019|website=Queen's Certificate in Law Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n==Rape myth acceptance==\n===Measures===\nIn 1980, Martha R. Burt introduced the Rape Myth Acceptance Scale (RMA, or RMAS).<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=hb>{{cite book |first=Carole A. |last=Beere |title=Sex and Gender Issues: A Handbook of Tests and Measures |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |url= https://archive.org/details/sexand_bee_1990_00_5030 |url-access=registration |via=Internet Archive |page=[https://archive.org/details/sexand_bee_1990_00_5030/page/400 400]|isbn=9780313274626 |year=1990 }}</ref> The scale was the first method for measuring an individual's level of belief in rape myths, and became the most widely used.<ref name=\"irma1999\"/> Using Burt's method, rape myth acceptance is measured by asking subjects 19 questions. The first 10 questions each consist of a statement which suggests that rape victims are responsible for their own rape, and ask the subject to assess its truthfulness, rating each statement on a seven-point scale from \"strongly agree\" to \"strongly disagree.\" The 11th statement tests for the inverse of this idea, asking whether or not it is true that any woman can be raped. The remaining questions ask test subjects to guess the proportion of reported rapes that are false, and assess whether they are more or less likely to believe a rape victim based on the victim's personal characteristics (for example, their gender, their race or ethnicity, their age, or their relationship to the test subject).<ref name=\"hb\"/>\n\nBurt's original study concluded that many Americans believed in rape myths. More than half of the individuals sampled in her original survey had agreed that \"a woman who goes to the home or apartment of a man\" on the first date \"implies she is willing to have sex,\" and that in the majority of rapes \"the victim was promiscuous or had a bad reputation.\" More than half of Burt's respondents had suggested 50% or more of reported rapes were reported \"only because the woman was trying to get back at a man\" or \"trying to cover up an illegitimate pregnancy.\"<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/>\n\nAnother measure is the 45-item Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale (IRMA), developed by Diana L. Payne, Kimberly A. Lonsway, and Louise F. Fitzgerald in 1999.<ref name=\"irma1999\">{{cite journal |title=Rape Myth Acceptance: Exploration of Its Structure and Its Measurement Using the ''Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale'' |first1=Diana L. |last1=Payne |first2=Kimberly A. |last2=Lonsway |first3=Louise F. |last3=Fitzgerald |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |volume= 33 |issue=1 |date=March 1999 |pages=27\u201368 |doi=10.1006/jrpe.1998.2238|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0815388f3263ea1b4eaf7facb5e23defdb80bbcc }}</ref> They concluded that \"rape myth acceptance is most adequately conceptualized as consisting of both a general component and seven distinct myth components: ''She asked for it; It wasn\u2019t really rape; He didn\u2019t mean to; She really wanted it; She lied; Rape is a trivial event;'' and ''Rape is a deviant event''\"<ref name=\"irma1999\"/>\n\nThe developers of IRMA analyzed responses to a pool of 95 statements about rape to create their scale.<ref name=\"irma1999\" />\n\nBased on the Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale, the Chinese Rape Myth Acceptance Scale (CRMA) is a culturally-specific myth scale that measures acceptance of rape myths in Chinese society. The scale operates under a culturally-adapted definition of rape, specifically, in China the legal definition of rape makes no provision for marital rape and does not apply to male victims. Additionally, the definition excludes \u201ctypes of coercive sexual behavior, such as other forms of penetrative sex, including oral sex, anal sex, and penetrations of the vagina or anus by other body parts like fingers or other objects.\u201d The CRMA retains 25 of 45 items from the IRMA scale and produces a five-factor structure. These myth component factors are: rape victims want to be raped; rape allegations are often false; rape must involve violence; victims are responsible for being raped; and, the motivation to rape is understandable.<ref>Xue J, Fang G, Huang H, Cui N, Rhodes KV, Gelles R. Rape myths and the cross-cultural adaptation of the Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale in China. Journal of Interpersonal Violence. 2016 5. [Epub ahead of print]. DOI: 10.1177/0886260516651315</ref>\n\n===Media influence on rape myth acceptance===\nA 2013 online survey of freshmen at a northwestern university{{which|date=June 2018}} in the United States suggested that women who consumed mainstream sports programming were more likely to accept rape myths, while for both men and women exposure to sports programming decreased the likelihood they would express an intention to intervene if they saw a sexual assault.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hust |first=Stacey J. T. |last2=Lei |first2=Ming |last3=Ren |first3=Chunbo |last4=Chang |first4=Hua |last5=McNab |first5=Anna L. |last6=Marett |first6=Emily G. |last7=Fitts Willoughby |first7=Jessica |date=1 November 2013 |title=The Effects of Sports Media Exposure on College Students' Rape Myth Beliefs and Intentions to Intervene in a Sexual Assault |journal=Mass Communication and Society |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=762\u2013786 |doi=10.1080/15205436.2013.816737 |issn=1520-5436 }}</ref> Another survey{{which|date=June 2018}} carried out online on a research panel in 2011 found that watching soap operas is associated with higher rape myth acceptance, while the reverse was true of watching crime shows.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Television's Role in the Culture of Violence Toward Women: A Study of Television Viewing and the Cultivation of Rape Myth Acceptance in the United States |first1=LeeAnn |last1=Kahlor |first2=Matthew S. |last2=Eastin |journal=Journal of Broadcasting & Electronic Media |volume=55 |issue=2 |date=2011 |pages=215\u2013231 |doi=10.1080/08838151.2011.566085}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rape culture]]\n*[[Slut-shaming]]\n*[[Sexual objectification]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Public opinion]]\n[[Category:Rape]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|misconceptions about rape|rape in mythology|List of rape victims from ancient history and mythology}}\n{{Tone|date=November 2017|reason=Unencyclopedic tone in various ways: reads like a brochure, uses informal wording (MOS:WE), and emotive language; making way too many assumptions about gender and age (\"women\") of victims; assumes men are always the perpetrators, presenting \"patriarchy\" arguments in Wikipedia's own voice; etc., etc.  Needs a thorough copyedit.}}\n{{Rape}}\n'''Rape myths''' are [[prejudice|prejudicial]], [[stereotype]]d and false beliefs about [[sexual assault]]s, rapists, and rape victims. They often serve to excuse sexual aggression, create hostility toward victims, and bias criminal prosecution.<ref name=\"Martha Burt\">{{Cite journal |last=Burt |first=Martha R. |title=Cultural myths and supports for rape |journal=[[Journal of Personality and Social Psychology]] |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=217\u2013230 |via=[[PsycINFO|PsycNET]] |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.38.2.217 |pmid=7373511 |date=February 1980}}</ref><ref name=wvu>{{cite web |title=Rape Myths and Facts |author=<!--Staff writers(s); no by-line.--> |date=2012 |url= http://well.wvu.edu/articles/rape_myths_and_facts |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170420122045/http://well.wvu.edu/articles/rape_myths_and_facts |archive-date=20 April 2017 |url-status=dead |work=Well.WVU.edu |publisher=[[West Virginia University]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HSKS\">{{Cite journal |title=Rape Myth Consistency and Gender Differences in Perceiving Rape Victims: A Meta-analysis |author=Hockett, Smith, Klausing, and Saucier |journal=Violence Against Women |date=2016 |volume=22 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013167 |doi=10.1177/1077801215607359 |pmid=26446194 }}</ref>\n\nExtensive research has been conducted about types, acceptance, and impact of rape myths.<ref name=\"RM\">{{cite journal |last1=Lonsway |first1=K. A. |last2=Fitzgerald |first2=L. F. |title=Rape Myths: In Review |journal=Psychology of Women Quarterly |volume=18 |issue=2 |date=1994 |pages=133\u2013164 |doi=10.1111/j.1471-6402.1994.tb00448.x}}</ref> Rape myths significantly influence the perspectives of jurors, investigative agencies, judges, perpetrators, and victims.<ref name=\"Temkin\">{{Cite journal |last=Temkin |first=Jennifer |title='And Always Keep A-hold of Nurse, for Fear of Finding Something Worse': Challenging Rape Myths in the Courtroom |url= http://openaccess.city.ac.uk/2527/1/NCLR1304_05.pdf|journal=New Criminal Law Review |volume=13 |issue=4 |page=710  |doi=10.1525/nclr.2010.13.4.710 |year=2010}}</ref> False views about rape lead to [[victim blaming]], shaming, questioning of the victim's honesty, and other problems. Determination of the guilt of the accused, and sentencing for sexual crimes, are also influenced by these beliefs.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Discretion, Discrimination and the Rule of Law |last=Satish |first=Mrinal |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |date=2016 |isbn= |pages=}}</ref>{{page needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Development of the concept==\nRape myths originate from various cultural stereotypes, such as traditional [[gender role]]s, acceptance of interpersonal violence, and misunderstanding the nature of sexual assault.<ref name=\"Martha Burt\" /> [[Matthew Hale (jurist)|Matthew Hale]], a British jurist in the 17<sup>th</sup> century, suggests that rape is \u201can accusation easily to be made and hard to be proved and harder to be defended against by the party accused, tho [''sic''] never so innocent\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=Dawn Rae|title=Rape in Chicago: Race, Myth and the Courts|publisher=University of Illinois Press|year=2012|isbn=|location=Urbana|pages=1}}</ref> His historical thoughts invisibly support many rape myths we see today, and continue to be reproduced in rape trials.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nRape myths first became a topic of research during the 1970s, when a number of studies and books explored the concept.<ref name=\"Brownmiller1975\">{{cite book|author=Susan Brownmiller|title=Against Our Will: Men, Women, and Rape|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qXhzjM8b_VUC|year=1975|publisher=Fawcett Columbine|isbn=978-0-449-90820-4}}</ref><ref>HS Feild, \"Attitudes toward rape: A Comparative Analysis of Police, Rapists, Crisis Counselors, and Citizens,\" ''Journal of Personality and Social Psychology,'' 36 (2), 1978: 166- 179.</ref><ref name=\"Schwen\">{{cite journal |last1=Schwendinger |first1=Julia R. |last2=Schwendinger |first2=Herman |date=1974 |title=Rape Myths: In Legal, Theoretical, and Everyday Practice |url= |journal=Crime and Social Justice |volume=1 |issue= |pages=18\u201326 |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> In 1974, for example, feminist writer [[Susan Brownmiller]] decried \"male myths of rape\" which \"deliberately obscure the true nature of rape\" in her book ''[[Against Our Will|Against Our Will: Men, Women and Rape]]''.<ref name=\"Brownmiller1975\"/> The same year, criminologists Julia and Herman Schwendinger studied common misconceptions about rape, including the notion that rape was impossible - i.e., that any woman who really wanted to could prevent a rape - the idea victims of rape were \"asking for it,\" and the idea that men rape because of \"uncontrollable passions.\" They termed these misconceptions \"sexist myths\" which \"influence the treatment of women victims.\"<ref name=\"Schwen\"/> Both Brownmiller's work and the Schwendingers' study suggested that rape myths perpetuated male violence against women by placing blame on the victim, excusing the rapist, and minimizing or justifying the act of rape.<ref name=\"irma1999\"/>\n\nIn 1980, Martha Burt published the first major study of rape myth acceptance.<ref name=\"irma1999\"/> Burt defined rape myths as \"prejudicial, stereotyped and false beliefs about rape, rape victims and rapists\" which create \"a climate hostile to rape victims.\"<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/> Burt's definition has been widely used.<ref name=\"Bohner\">{{cite book |last1=Bohner |first1=Gerd |last2=Eyssel|first2=Friederike|last3=Pina|first3=Afroditi|last4=Viki|first4=Tendayi|last5=Siebler|first5=Frank|editor1-last=Horvath|editor1-first=Miranda A.H.|editor2-last=Brown|editor2-first=Jennifer M.|date=2013 |title=Rape: Challenging Contemporary Thinking |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=SpkzxXmtI50C&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= |publisher=Willan (Routledge)|pages=17\u201345 |isbn=978-1134026463}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Kimberly A. Lonsway and Louise F. Fitzgerald defined rape myths as \"attitudes and beliefs that are generally false but are widely and persistently held, and that serve to deny and justify male sexual aggression against women.\"<ref>Kimberly A. Lonsway, Louise F. Fitzgerald, \"Rape Myths: In Review\" ''Psychology of Women Quarterly'' 18 (2), June 1994: 133-164.</ref>\n\nSome scholars, such as [[Gerd Bohner]]  and Heike Gerger, have argued that descriptors such as \"false\" and \"widely held\" should not be included in a formal definition of what rape myths are since myths are often constructed in a way that are impossible to falsify, (as in the example, \"many women ''secretly'' desire to be raped,\" where \"secret\" desire cannot be disproven) and the degree to which rape myths are \"widely held\" or accepted may vary over time.<ref name=\"Bohner\"/> Bohner has offered an alternative definition of rape myths as \"descriptive or prescriptive beliefs about rape (ie, about its causes, context, consequences, perpetrators, victims and their interaction) that serve to deny, downplay or justify sexual violence against women.\"<ref>Gerd Bohner, ''Vergewaltigungsmythen'' (Rape Myths) Verlag Empirische P\u00e4dagogik, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"Bohner\"/>\n\nWhile scholars disagree somewhat on how to precisely define the concept of rape myths, and rape myths can vary across different cultures and societies, there is a general consensus that there are four basic types of rape myths: those that blame the victim for their rape, those that express doubt or disbelief about victim's reports of a rape, those that exonerate the rapist, and those that suggest that only a certain type of woman gets raped.<ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref>Grubb, Amy & Turner, Emily. (2012). \"Attribution of blame in rape cases: A review of the impact of rape myth acceptance, gender role conformity and substance use on victim blaming\" ''Aggression and Violent Behavior'' 17 (5) 443-452.\n*\"Rape myths vary among societies and cultures. However, they consistently follow a pattern whereby, they blame the victim for their rape, express a disbelief in claims of rape, exonerate the perpetrator and allude that only certain types of women are raped.\"</ref>\n\nLonsway, Fitzgerald and Diana L. Payne wrote in 1999 that the term \"rape myth\" does not imply that a given scenario ''never'' occurs, and \"it is clear that any individual instance might conform to the characteristics described in cultural male mythology,\" since there is \"undeniably some percentage of women\" who have made false reports of rape, and there are \"certain situational or personal characteristics that differentiate women who have been raped from those who have not.\" They argue, however, that rape myths are \"generally false\" in nature, and function to deny and justify the victimization of women.<ref name=\"irma1999\">{{cite journal |title=Rape Myth Acceptance: Exploration of Its Structure and Its Measurement Using the ''Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale'' |first1=Diana L. |last1=Payne |first2=Kimberly A. |last2=Lonsway |first3=Louise F. |last3=Fitzgerald |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |volume= 33 |issue=1 |date=March 1999 |pages=27\u201368 |doi=10.1006/jrpe.1998.2238|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0815388f3263ea1b4eaf7facb5e23defdb80bbcc }}</ref> \n\n=== Heteronormative discourses ===\n[[Heteronormativity]] and associated discourses undergird and perpetuate many rape myths. The construction of the male sexual subject and female passive object serves to de-legitimatize allegations of sexual assault that are contrary to heterosexual norms, such as where women are perpetrators and men are victims. Through the \u201cmale sexual drive discourse\u201d, it is thought that men are always ready and desiring sex, and women \u201cactivate their interest\u201d,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gavey|first=Nicola|title=Just sex? The cultural scaffolding of rape|publisher=Routledge|year=2019|isbn=|edition=Second|location=Abingdon, Oxon|pages=99}}</ref> which can invalidate experiences that do not confirm to this discourse. Similarly, the \u201chave/hold discourse\u201d produces women as asexual, and heterosexual pleasure comes secondary to the ultimate goal of having a relationship and family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gavey|first=|title=Just sex|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100}}</ref>\n\n==Common rape myths==\nCommon rape myths may include:\n*That women commonly or routinely lie about rape.<ref name=\"EMH\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Mental Health|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5aLxBQAAQBAJ&pg=RA3-PA15|date=26 August 2015|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-12-397753-3|pages=3}}\n*\"Common rape myths may include: women often lie about rape, a victim's clothing can precipitate a sexual assault, rape is the fault of the victim if she was intoxicated, and when a male pays for a date, the woman is expected to reciprocate with sexual intercourse.\"</ref><ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\">{{cite book|author1=Paula K. Lundberg-Love|author2=Shelly L. Marmion|title=\"Intimate\" Violence Against Women: When Spouses, Partners, Or Lovers Attack|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=OnEq_IbDSUQC&lpg=PA59&pg=PA60#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-98967-5|pages=59\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\">{{cite book|author1=Holly Johnson|author2=Bonnie S. Fisher|author3=Veronique Jaquier|title=Critical Issues on Violence Against Women: International Perspectives and Promising Strategies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pD62BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA96|date=5 December 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-00603-7|pages=96\u2013}}\n*\"Some rape myths include: that women fantasize about being raped; that women routinely lie about rape; that men cannot rape their intimate partners; that rape is simply unwanted sex and not a violent crime; and that victims are usually attacked by strangers.\"</ref><ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref name=Hayes>Rebecca M. Hayes1, Katherine Lorenz2, Kristin A. Bell, \"Victim Blaming Others: Rape Myth Acceptance and the Just World Belief,\" ''Feminist Criminology'' 8 (3), April 2013: 202-220.\n*\"Common rape myths include: the misconception that the victim\u2019s clothing precipitated the assault, that women often lie about rape, that rape is the victim\u2019s fault if they were intoxicated at the time of the assault, and; when a male pays for a date, the woman is expected to reciprocate with sexual intercourse.</ref><ref name=\"irma1999\"/><ref name=Rich>{{cite book|author=Karen Rich|title=Interviewing Rape Victims: Practice and Policy Issues in an International Context|date=2014|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|isbn=9781137353221}}\n*\"Rape Myths include, but are not limited to, each of the following statements or beliefs: Rape is rare, Rape is not harmful, Most victims lie about rape, Some victims deserve to be raped, Women drive men to rape them by wearing provocative attire, Rape is a crime of passion, Rapists are mentally retarded/seriously mentally ill... Only certain kinds of women are raped, A man cannot 'rape' his wife, Some women secretly want to be raped.\"</ref><ref name=Reddington/>\n*That what the victim is wearing can lead to a sexual assault, or that rape is the victim's fault if they wore revealing clothes.<ref name=\"EMH\"/><ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref name=Hayes/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref>Moor, Avigail (2010). She Dresses to Attract, He Perceives Seduction: A Gender Gap in Attribution of Intent to Women\u2019s Revealing Style of Dress and its Relation to Blaming the Victims of Sexual Violence. Journal of International Women's Studies, 11(4), 115-127.</ref><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=ymrk2002/><ref name=Rich/>\n*That victims bear responsibility for an assault if they were intoxicated when it happened.<ref name=\"EMH\"/><ref>Hayes, R. M., Lorenz, K., & Bell, K. A. (2013). Victim blaming others: Rape myth acceptance and the just world belief. Feminist Criminology, 1557085113484788.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |first1=Vanessa |last1=Munro |first2=Emily |last2=Finch |date= |title=Juror Stereotypes and Blame Attribution in Rape Cases Involving Intoxicants |url= |journal=British Journal of Criminology |volume=25|issue=1|pages=25\u201338 }}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants=R v. Malone |reporter=2 Cr. App. R. |volume=447 |date=1998|url=http://ww3.lawschool.cornell.edu/AvonResources/R-v-Malone.pdf}}</ref>\n*That most rapes are committed by strangers.<ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"doi.org\">Ben-David, S. & Schneider, O. Sex Roles (2005) 53: 385. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11199-005-6761-4</ref> (In reality, most rapes are committed by friends, family, or other individuals known to the victim.)<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://ncrb.nic.in/StatPublications/CII/CII2015/FILES/Compendium-15.11.16.pdf |title=Crime in India 2015 Compendium |last= |first= |date= |work=NCRB.NIC.in |publisher=National Crime Records Bureau, India |access-date=March 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Temkin\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ellison |first=Louis |title=Reacting to Rape: Exploring Mock Jurors' Assessments of Complainant Credibility |url= |journal=The British Journal of Criminology |volume=49 |issue=2 |page=202 |doi=10.1093/bjc/azn077 |year=2008}}</ref><ref name=Reddington/>\n*That when a male pays for a dinner or date, a woman is expected to reciprocate with intercourse.<ref name=\"EMH\"/><ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=Hayes/>\n*That women who are raped often deserve it - particularly if they entered a man's home or got in his car, or that such actions indicate consent to sex.<ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=Rich/>\n*That it is not rape unless the victim fights/physically resists, or that it is not rape unless the victim is physically coerced or injured.<ref name=\"Kennedy 2012 309\u2013311\">{{cite journal |last=Kennedy |first=K. M. |title=The relationship of victim injury to the progression of sexual crimes through the criminal justice system |journal=Journal of Forensic and Legal Medicine |date=2012 |volume=19 |issue=6 |pages=309\u2013311 |doi=10.1016/j.jflm.2012.04.033|pmid=22847045 |hdl=10379/12225 |url=https://www.lenus.ie/bitstream/10147/266322/1/RelationshipofVictim.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=ymrk2002>Yancey-Martin, Reynolds, Keith,\"Gender Bias and Feminist Consciousness among Judges and Attorneys: A Standpoint Theory Analysis\", 2002, {{doi|10.1086/337941}}</ref> (In reality, many rapes do not involve physical coercion, as in cases where the victim is impaired/unconscious, or where an unequal power relationship forces the victim to submit.)<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.lawctopus.com/academike/section-375-analysis-of-provisions-relating-to-rape/ |first=Soumya Singh |last=Chauhan |title=Section 375: Analysis of Provisions Relating to Rape |date=14 February 2015 |work=Academike |publisher=Lawctopus |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite court |url= https://indiankanoon.org/doc/1607781/ |litigants=Rao Harnarain Singh, Sheoji Singh, et al. v. The State |date=12 August 1957 |court=Punjab-Haryana High Court, India |reporter=AIR 1958 P H 123; 1958 CriLJ 563. |via=IndianKanoon.org |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Evaluating Stranger and Acquaintance Rape: The Role of Benevolent Sexism in Perpetrator Blame and Recommended Sentence Length |url= |journal=Law and Human Behavior |volume=28|issue= 3|pages= 295\u2013303|doi= 10.1023/B:LAHU.0000029140.72880.69|pmid= 15264448|year= 2004|last1= Viki|first1= G. Tendayi|last2= Abrams|first2= Dominic|last3= Masser|first3= Barbara}}</ref><ref name=\"Kennedy 2012 309\u2013311\"/>\n*That a woman should be able to avoid rape by \"fighting off\" the rapist, and that she has the responsibility to do so.<ref name=\"Temkin\" /><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/>\n*That some women secretly want to be raped.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=Rich/><ref name=Reddington/><ref name=\"Edwards 761\u2013773\">{{Cite journal|last=Edwards|first=Katie M.|last2=Turchik|first2=Jessica A.|last3=Dardis|first3=Christina M.|last4=Reynolds|first4=Nicole|last5=Gidycz|first5=Christine A.|date=December 2011|title=Rape Myths: History, Individual and Institutional-Level Presence, and Implications for Change|journal=Sex Roles|volume=65|issue=11\u201312|pages=761\u2013773|doi=10.1007/s11199-011-9943-2|issn=0360-0025}}</ref>\n*That it is impossible to rape one's wife or intimate partner.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=Rich/>\n*That rape is simply unwanted sex, not a violent crime.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/>\n*That women \"ask for\" rape - for example, by flirting, dressing provocatively, consuming alcohol or behaving promiscuously<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/> - or that only certain \"kinds of\" women (i.e., \"bad girls\") are raped.<ref name=\"Bohner\"/><ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=\"irma1999\"/><ref name=\"McMahon\">{{Cite journal |author-last1=McMahon |author-first1=Sarah|author-last2=Farmer|author-first2=G. Lawrence |date=June 2011 |title=An Updated Measure for Assessing Subtle Rape Myths |url= |journal=Social Work Research |volume=35|issue=2|pages=71\u201381  |doi=10.1093/swr/35.2.71}}</ref><ref name=Rich/><ref name=Reddington/>\n*That men are unable to control themselves once they become sexually excited, that women are responsible for rape if they allow things to go too far,<ref name=\"Lundberg-LoveMarmion2006\"/><ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=ymrk2002/> or that consent to kissing, petting, etc. constitutes consent to intercourse.<ref name=\"Cocker\">{{Cite journal |last=Cocker |first=Ann |date=2005 |title=PTSD Symptoms Among Men and Women Survivors of Intimate Partner Violence: The Role of Risk and Protective Factors |url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1c3864218194aa24347e67761cb3115b0cf9973e|journal=Violence & Victims |volume=20 |issue=6 |page=625 |doi=10.1891/0886-6708.20.6.625 }}</ref>\n*That women commonly falsely allege rape out of spite, to overcome guilt after a sexual encounter they regret, to cover up an unwanted pregnancy, or for attention.<ref name=\"Scott-Snyder2017\">{{cite book|author=Stephanie Scott-Snyder|title=Introduction to Forensic Psychology: Essentials for Law Enforcement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ka_ZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT103|date=6 January 2017|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-315-29853-5|pages=103\u2013}}</ref><ref name=ymrk2002/>\n*That rape must be sexually motivated. Many researchers have concluded that power and/or anger, not sex, are often the dominant motivator of rapes.<ref name=\"doi.org\"/><ref name=aiws>{{cite journal |url= https://uiowa.edu/crisp/sites/uiowa.edu.crisp/files/6.8.pdf |title=Perceived Motivation for Rape: Gender Differences in Beliefs About Female and Male Rape |first1=Irina |last1=Anderson |first2=Victoria |last2=Swainson |journal=Current Research in Social Psychology |volume=6 |issue=8 |date=17 April 2001 |publisher=[[University of Iowa]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n*That most rapists are psychotic or mentally ill.<ref name=aiws>{{cite journal |url= https://uiowa.edu/crisp/sites/uiowa.edu.crisp/files/6.8.pdf |title=Perceived Motivation for Rape: Gender Differences in Beliefs About Female and Male Rape |first1=Irina |last1=Anderson |first2=Victoria |last2=Swainson |journal=Current Research in Social Psychology |volume=6 |issue=8 |date=17 April 2001 |publisher=[[University of Iowa]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=Rich/><ref name=Reddington>{{cite book|title=Sexual Assault: The Victims, the Perpetrators, and the Criminal Justice System|author1-last=Reddington|author1-first=Frances P.|author2-last=Kreisel|author2-first=Betsy Wright|publisher=Carolina Academic Press|date=2009|isbn=9781594605772}}</ref>\n*That consent to one sexual encounter constitutes consent to another (i.e., that it cannot be rape if the victim and rapist have previously had consensual sex).<ref name=\"Cocker\" />\n*That \"real\" victims report rape immediately. (In reality, victims often don't report rapes immediately due to societal pressure, possible backlash, and trauma such as rape related [[post traumatic stress disorder]], also known as [[rape trauma syndrome]]. Victims of rape may also feel feelings of guilt and shame which deter them from reporting the crime, or doing so promptly.)<ref>{{cite journal|author=Neil Kibble|title=Case Comments: R v. Doody [2009]|journal=Criminal Law Review|volume=2009|date=2009|pages=590\u2013597}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Chennels |first=Rebecca |date= |title=Sentencing: The 'real rape' myth |url= |journal=Agenda: Empowering Women for Gender Equity |volume=82 |page=23 }}</ref><ref name=\"HSKS\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://in.reuters.com/article/india-delhi-gang-rape-women-safety-polic/analysis-how-indias-police-and-judiciary-fail-rape-victims-idINDEE90F0AY20130116 |title=Analysis: How India's police and judiciary fail rape victims |last=Bhalla |first=Nita |work=In.Reuters.com |publisher=[[Reuters]] |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/182369.pdf |title=The Sexual Victimization of College Women |last1=Fisher |first1=Bonnie S. |last2=Cullen |first2=Francis T. |last3=Turner |first3=Michael G. |date=December 2000 |location=Washington DC |publisher=[[National Institute of Justice]] / [[Bureau of Justice Statistics]] |via=NCJRS.gov ([[National Criminal Justice Reference Service]]) |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://globalnews.ca/news/1845136/why-dont-women-report-rape-because-most-get-no-justice-when-they-do/ |title=Why don't women report rape? Because most get no justice when they do |work=Global News |access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rape myths involving male victims===\nMost of the rape myths listed above deal with the rape of women by men. There has been less research on perceptions of rapes of male victims, whether by women or by other men. The following have been identified:<ref name=COR>Kristine M. Chapleau, Debra L. Oswald, Brenda L. Russell, \"Male Rape Myths: The Role of Gender, Violence, and Sexism\", Journal of Interpersonal Violence, Volume: 23 issue: 5, page(s): 600-615, {{doi|10.1177/0886260507313529}}</ref> Rape myths can stem from the media and are largely held by the general population. Research suggests that a common myth is that men experience little trauma when perpetrated by a woman.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hammond |first1=Laura |last2=Loannou |first2=Maria |last3=Fewster |first3=Martha |title=Perception of male rape and sexual assault in a male sample from the United Kingdom: Barriers to reporting and the impacts of victimization |journal=Journal of Investigative Psychology and Offender Profiling |volume=14 |issue=2 |pages=133\u2013149 |date=June 1, 2017 |doi=10.1002/jip.1462 |url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/29241/7/Perceptions%20of%20Male%20Rape%20and%20Sexual%20Assault.pdf }}</ref>\n\n*That being raped by a male attacker is synonymous with the loss of masculinity.\n*That men who are sexually assaulted by men must be gay.\n*That men are incapable of functioning sexually unless they are sexually aroused.\n*That men cannot be forced to have sex against their will.\n*That men are less affected by sexual assault than women.\n*That men are in a constant state of readiness to accept any sexual opportunity.\n*That a man is expected to be able to defend himself against sexual assault.\nThey may also include the following beliefs:<ref name=SJSJ>{{cite journal | last1 = Struckman-Johnson | first1 = C. | last2 = Struckman-Johnson | first2 = D. | year = 1992 | title = Acceptance of male rape myths among college men and women | url = | journal = Sex Roles | volume = 27 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 85\u2013100 | doi=10.1007/bf00290011}}</ref><ref name=COR/><ref name=\"Edwards 761\u2013773\"/>\n\n*\"Denial\": That male rape does not exist.  \n*\"Blame\": That male rape is victim's fault.\n*\"Trauma\": That men are less traumatized by the rape.\n\nThe latter two categories show higher myth acceptance in the case when the perpetrator is a female.<ref name=SJSJ/><ref name=COR/> Male victims are also placed with the blame of their rape more often than female victims.<ref name=\"Turchik 211\u2013226\">{{Cite journal|last=Turchik|first=Jessica A.|last2=Edwards|first2=Katie M.|date=April 2012|title=Myths about male rape: A literature review.|journal=Psychology of Men & Masculinity|volume=13|issue=2|pages=211\u2013226|doi=10.1037/a0023207|issn=1939-151X}}</ref>\n\n=== Rape Myths and Disabilities ===\n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Benedet |first1=Janine |last2=Grant |first2=Isabel |title=Sexual Assault and the Meaning of Power and Authority for Women with Mental Disabilities |journal=Springer Science+Business Media Dordrecht 2014 |date=4 July 2014 |pages=131-154}}</ref>\nWhile disabled people are viewed as asexual, they are also hypersexualized which can encourage sexual abuse.  Disabled people are desexualized and hypersexualized at the same time which they both work against the person. People living with disabilities are viewed on a binary scale as they are seen as all or nothing. If they are seen as capable, they are always seen as capable and if you are seen as incapable they are always denied sex. Therefore the law needs to think in a situational way as people with disabilities have different levels of capabilities, \u201cLegally, it may cause us to miss the multifaceted ways in which people with mental disabilities resist or object to sexual assault and also to assume that compliance represents consent rather than acquiescence in the face of coercion or exploitative inducements\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Benedet |first1=Janine |last2=Grant |first2=Isabel |title=Sexual Assault and the Meaning of Power and Authority for Women with Mental Disabilities |journal=Springer Science+Business Media Dordrecht 2014 |date=4 July 2014 |pages=131-154}}</ref>. The view that they are asexual or hypersexual creates the idea that they cannot be victims of sexual violence, labeling them as an unrapable group. This myth is further articulated within the Benedet and Grant article, they discuss a prominent rape myth that labels people of disabilities to be \u201clucky\u201d to get any male attention, including coerced and nonconsensual sex. Any sex, however coercive, is construed as better than no sex which was illustrated by Chenoweth\n\n=== Transgender Rape Myths ===\nAs trans-gender people challenge dominant gender norms, this often leaves them in a place of marginalization. Transgender people are the most likely to face violence and backlash as people perceive them as inherently deceptive as they are said to be concealing their \u201ctrue sex\u201d. This is a very transphobic assumption that rationalizes the violence against trans people (mainly trans women) and the criminalization of trans people (mainly trans men). \n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schilt |first1=Kristen |last2=Westbrook |first2=Lauren |title=DOING GENDER, DOING HETERONORMATIVITY |journal=GENDER & SOCIETY |date=August 4, 2009 |volume=23 |pages=440-464}}</ref>\n\n\u201cPenis Panic\u201d emerges in the discourse surrounding gender-neutral washrooms, due to the belief that men (and their penis) have a \u201cpropensity to rape\u201d <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Westbrook|first=Laurel|last2=Schilt|first2=Kristen|date=2014|title=Doing gender, determining gender: Transgender people, gender panics, and the maintenance of the sex/gender/sexuality system|url=|journal=Gender and Society|volume=Vol 28, No. 1|pages=32 - 57|via=}}</ref> . Therefore transgender women are portrayed, due to their penis, as a threat to women if they share the same washroom. Susan Brownmiller explores the biological determinism that defines rape due to the structural differences in men versus women (<ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Cahill|first=Ann|title=Rethinking Rape|publisher=Cornell University Press|year=2001|isbn=|location=Ithaca|pages=21}}</ref> This myth is furthered by the idea that allowing transgender people to use the restroom that aligns with their perceived gender will end up allowing male sexual predators into women\u2019s bathrooms. \n\nAnother common myth is the belief that no one wants to sexually assault a transgender person due to their identity. But that is not true, as transgender folks tend to be more vulnerable they could be more at risk to face sexual violence, especially as a form of hate crime. A common misconception is that sexual assault is primarily about sexual attraction, but rather it is about the dynamics of power and control over another person.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foundation |first1=LGBT |title=A guide for trans people who have been affected by sexual violence |url=https://www.gendergp.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Guide-for-trans-people-affected-by-sexual-violence-1.pdf |website=lgbt.foundation/counselling |publisher=LGBT Foundation |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Rape Myths in the Prison System ===\nActions such as strip searches, body-cavity searches, and non-consensual medical interventions within the prison system are not violent acts is a common myth. Looking at similar actions occurring outside the prison shows nothing less than sexual assault as these acts lack consent, often have present resistance, and can have traumatizing effects <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref>. And like many acts of sexual violence, these types of searches are also a form of exerting control over another individual.\n\nIt is believed that some prisoners have brought sexual abuse on themselves or deserve the violence they face through the crime they committed that landed them in prison, i.e. sex offenders or child molesters<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ferranti |first1=Seth |title=Why Are So Many Sex Offenders Getting Murdered in California's Prisons? |url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/ppmjy8/why-sex-offenders-are-getting-slaughtered-in-california-prisons-218 |website=VICE |publisher=VICE |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>. But that is not true, no one deserves to be a victim of sexual violence. The prison systems have normalized sexual violence through staff interactions (abuse of power, strip searches, body cavity searches, and other nonconsensual acts), as well as ignored the violence occurring between the inmates <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref> <ref>{{cite web |last1=Wakefield |first1=Jonny |title=Alberta prisoners made 67 allegations of sexual assault in the last five fiscal years; Only one resulted in a criminal charge |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/insight/violent-and-coercive-sexual-assault-behind-bars-is-a-taboo-topic-but-statistics-tell-only-part-of-the-story/ |website=Edmonton Journal |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>. The normalization of sexual violence within prisons allows the system and power dynamics to be upheld. In situations where sexual violence becomes normalized, it desensitizes people to the issue, creating the belief that prisoners will come out more criminal. The negative effects to the normalization of sexual violence in prisons do not stop there, it allows many allegations to go unnoticed, leaving many victims without prosecution and the issue to not be viewed as a systemic problem <ref>{{cite web |last1=Wakefield |first1=Jonny |title=Alberta prisoners made 67 allegations of sexual assault in the last five fiscal years; Only one resulted in a criminal charge |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/insight/violent-and-coercive-sexual-assault-behind-bars-is-a-taboo-topic-but-statistics-tell-only-part-of-the-story/ |website=Edmonton Journal |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>..  \n\nThe Prison Rape Elimination Act (PREA) helps to ensure prisoner's safety against sexual violence by, \u201climiting circumstances where prisoners experience touching, viewing, or other manipulation of their genitals, anus, buttocks, or breasts against their will\u201d <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref>.  Although this is not the case, as it rather punishes consensual interactions amongst the prisoners, resulting in the deeper issue of homophobia. Or it goes in the other direction of reducing sexual assault into consensual acts. PREA leaves many non-consensual acts virtually unregulated which go against its intended purpose.\n\nThe evil perpetrator / innocent victim dyad commonly found within the prison systems idea of sexual assault reduces violence to an individual act that occurs between two people. The prison systems, however, creates sexual violence as a \u201cgroup-based phenomenon that does group-based harm\u201d, which typically results in the reinforcement of hierarchies, fear amongst certain groups, and this belief that not all people deserve to have control over their bodies <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Arkles |first1=Gabriel |title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence |journal=Northeastern University Law Journal |date=2015 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=71-130}}</ref></ref>.\n\n=== Racial rape myths ===\nScholars have argued that [[racism]] remains a critical component of sexual violence discourse within the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arkles|first=Gabriel|date=2015|title=Regulating Prison Sexual Violence|url=|journal=Northeastern University Law Journal|volume=Vol. 7, No. 1|pages=71 - 130|via=}}</ref> Alcoff and Gray state that white victims who report they were raped by non-white perpetrators are more likely to be believed than non-white victims who report white perpetrators.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alcoff|first=Linda|last2=Gray|first2=Laura|date=Winter 1993|title=Survivor Discourse: Transgression or Recuperation?|url=|journal=Signs|volume=Vol 18, No. 2|pages=260 - 290|via=}}</ref> Not only are non-white bodies seen as not rapable, but non-white men are seen as sexually deviant, violent, and dangerous. In the context of African American men, Dawn Rae Flood argues that the history of race relations within America constructs accused African American men as guilty of any accusations against a white woman, because of their \u201cinherently criminal sexual nature\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFlood argues that under [[white supremacy]], black sexuality was constructed as \u201cforeign\u201d, \u201csavage\u201d, immoral, and predatory towards white women.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=4}}</ref> Rooted in slavery and the white slave owners\u2019 access to Black women, the \u201cJezebel\u201d rape myth portrays Black women as \u201cunrapable\u201d,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=12}}</ref> due to a belief that they are \u201csexually promiscuous\u201d and would not refuse to consent.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=77}}</ref> Black women are also portrayed as asexual, due to the \u201cmammy\u201d stereotype, which depicts them as motherly and lacking sexual characteristics.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flood|first=|title=Rape in Chicago|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=81}}</ref>\n\nSherene Razack argues that indigenous people are seen as hypersexual, and she argues that \u201cbodies in degenerate spaces\u201d lose their personhood due to the naturalization of violence, and in the context of indigenous sex workers, these women through being marked \u201cas a body to be violated\", become \u201cunrapable\u201d.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Razack|first=Sherene|date=2000|title=Gendered Racial Violence and Spatialized Justice: The Murder Pamela George|url=|journal=Canadian Journal of Law and Society|volume=Vol 15, No. 2|pages=91 - 130|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Marital rape myths ===\nJennifer Koshan states that many marital rape myths were born from British attitudes and laws during colonial times and were rationales that granted criminal immunity to husbands accused of marital rape.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=Jennifer|title=The Criminalisation of Marital Rape and Law Reform in Canada: A Modest Feminist Success Story in Combatting Marital Rape Myths in The Right to Say No: Marital Rape and Law Reform in Canada, Ghana, Kenya and Malawi|publisher=Hart Publishing|year=2017|isbn=|editor-last=Randall|editor-first=Melanie|location=Portland, Oregon|pages=144|editor-last2=Koshan|editor-first2=Jennifer|editor-last3=Nyaundi|editor-first3=Patricia}}</ref> Such myths include:\n\n* Women in intimate relationships are in a state of perpetual consent,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/marital-rape-myths-have-no-place-in-canadian-law/article36749822/|title=Marital rape myths have no place in Canadian law|last=Koshan|first=Jennifer|last2=Randall|first2=Melanie|date=2017|website=The Globe and Mail|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last3=Sheehy|first3=Elizabeth}}</ref> or the \u201cimplied consent theory\u201d.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=|title=The Criminalisation of Martial Rape|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=145}}</ref>\n* Wives could not be raped, because they joined \u201cthe person of her husband\u201d, or the \u201ctheory of coverture\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Wives became the property of their husband, and could be raped without regard for punishment.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* Women that consent to sex with their partner after being raped cannot claim to being raped.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Being raped by one\u2019s husband is \u201cless severe than being raped by a stranger.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=Jennifer|url=http://theequalityeffect.org/pdfs/maritalrapecanadexperience.pdf|title=The Legal Treatment of Marital Rape and Women\u2019s Equality: An Analysis of the Canadian Experience|publisher=The Equality Effect|year=2010|isbn=|location=Toronto|pages=50}}</ref>\n* Marital rape allegations are \u201cvengeful women crying rape\u201d,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Busby|first=Karen|date=2012|title=Every Breath You Take: Erotic Asphyxiation, Vengeful Wives, and Other Enduring Myths in Spousal Sexual Assault Prosecutions|url=|journal=Canadian Journal of Women and the Law|volume=Vol 24, Issue 2|pages=328 - 358|via=}}</ref> and women are \u201cprone to fabrication\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Koshan|first=|title=The Legal Treatment|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=57}}</ref>\n\n\n==Problems arising out of rape myths==\n\nThe prevalence of rape myths is a major reason for rape [[victim blaming]] and [[Social stigma|stigmatization]].<ref name=\"wvu\" /><ref name=\"HSKS\" /> Rape myths can cause victims of rape to blame themselves for their rape, or to not report their assault, and they can also shape the responses of judges and juries, causing a negative impact on rape victims.<ref name=Rich/> Some studies have shown that police officers are often distrustful of rape victims' account of their victimization, and that many of them believe some common rape myths.<ref name=\"JohnsonFisher2014\"/><ref name=Jordan>{{cite journal|author-last=Jordan|author-first=Jan|date=February 2004|title=Beyond Belief? Police, Rape, and Women's Credibility|journal=Criminology and Criminal Justice|volume=4|issue=1|pages=29\u201359|doi=10.1177/1466802504042222|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/291e2b1d81cc8afe17eaa2a95a62f631dde58823}}</ref><ref name=Page>{{cite journal|author-last=Page|author-first=Amy Dellinger|title=Gateway to Reform? Policy Implications of Police Officers' Attitudes Toward Rape|journal=American Journal of Criminal Justice|volume=33|issue=1|date=2008|pages=44\u201358|doi=10.1007/s12103-007-9024-9}}</ref> Also, many who believe even one rape myth typically also do not believe female rape myths any more or any less than male rape myths.<ref name=\"Turchik 211\u2013226\"/> Though, men are also more likely to warrant rape myths rather than women.<ref name=\"Edwards 761\u2013773\"/>\n\nDue to reported higher rape myth acceptance among males than females, as well as because of other gender-based differences in perceptions and standpoints, one analysis by Patricia Yancey Martin, John R. Reynolds and Shelley Keith suggested that \"a judiciary made up solely of men differs from one made up of more equal proportions of women and men\".<ref name=\"ymrk2002\" /><ref>{{cite book |first=Martha |last=Reeves |title=Women in Business: Theory and Cases |edition=2nd |date=2016 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=NqnZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT70 |page=70 |via=Google Books |access-date=7 November 2017|isbn=9781317363316 }}</ref> This commentary is furthered by the writings of Mallios and Meisner, who state that rape myth acceptance is problematic in judicial settings. They assert that ''[[voir dire]]'' can be used to curb jury bias related to preconceived notions regarding rape.<ref>Mallios C, Meisner T. Educating juries in sexual assault cases: Using voir dire to eliminate jury bias. Strategies: The Prosecutors\u2019 Newsletter on Violence Against Women, 2010; 2. http://www.aequitasresource.org/EducatingJuriesInSexualAssaultCasesPart1.pdf</ref> This problem is further heightened by the fact that investigative agencies, various participants in the Legal System, and points of contacts for rape victims, for example the nearest doctor, are likelier to be male, than female. The 2015 book ''Asking for It''&nbsp;by [[Kate Harding]] talks about common rape myths and about the differences between male and female rapes. One in five women and one in seventy-one men in the United States will find out what it's like to be raped, according to Harding. She writes, \"Women are no more important than any other potential victims, but we are the primary targets of the messages and myths that sustain rape culture. Anyone can be raped, but men aren't conditioned to live in terror of it, nor are they constantly warned that their clothing, travel choices, alcohol consumption, and expressions of sexuality are likely to bring violations upon them.\"<ref name=\"Harding\">{{Cite book |title=Asking for It |last=Harding |first=Kate |publisher=Da Capo Press |date=2015 |isbn=978-0-7382-1702-4 |location=Philadelphia |pages=}}</ref>{{rp|19}}\n\nSuch stereotypes reduce the inclination of victims to report instances of rape, harassment, and assault. This reduced reporting of crimes might present a rosy picture and would further the problem, by leading to beliefs that these crimes that are reported are fake, false, or unlikely to be true.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn ''Asking for It'', Harding writes of rape that \"we tend not to treat it as a serious crime unless there's simultaneously evidence of another one\".<ref name=\"Harding\"/>{{rp|11}}  The author also quotes psychologist [[David Lisak]]. He says that \"Ultimately, only a tiny handful of rapists ever serve time for rape, a shocking outcome given that we view rape as close kin to murder in the taxonomy of violent crime\".<ref name=\"Harding\"/>{{rp|11}}\n\n=== Twin myths ===\nThe ''twin myths'' suggest that a victim\u2019s previous sexual history i) makes them less believable, and/or ii) more likely to consent. Canadian law does allow for the inclusion of previous sexual history, but defence counsel must present a s.276 application and a hearing is held to ensure the evidence will not be used in the context of the twin myths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://certificate.queenslaw.ca/blog/the-supreme-court-sexual-assault-and-twin-myths|title=The Supreme Court, Sexual Assault and \"Twin Myths\"|last=Rawson|first=Kate|date=2019|website=Queen's Certificate in Law Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n==Rape myth acceptance==\n===Measures===\nIn 1980, Martha R. Burt introduced the Rape Myth Acceptance Scale (RMA, or RMAS).<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/><ref name=hb>{{cite book |first=Carole A. |last=Beere |title=Sex and Gender Issues: A Handbook of Tests and Measures |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |url= https://archive.org/details/sexand_bee_1990_00_5030 |url-access=registration |via=Internet Archive |page=[https://archive.org/details/sexand_bee_1990_00_5030/page/400 400]|isbn=9780313274626 |year=1990 }}</ref> The scale was the first method for measuring an individual's level of belief in rape myths, and became the most widely used.<ref name=\"irma1999\"/> Using Burt's method, rape myth acceptance is measured by asking subjects 19 questions. The first 10 questions each consist of a statement which suggests that rape victims are responsible for their own rape, and ask the subject to assess its truthfulness, rating each statement on a seven-point scale from \"strongly agree\" to \"strongly disagree.\" The 11th statement tests for the inverse of this idea, asking whether or not it is true that any woman can be raped. The remaining questions ask test subjects to guess the proportion of reported rapes that are false, and assess whether they are more or less likely to believe a rape victim based on the victim's personal characteristics (for example, their gender, their race or ethnicity, their age, or their relationship to the test subject).<ref name=\"hb\"/>\n\nBurt's original study concluded that many Americans believed in rape myths. More than half of the individuals sampled in her original survey had agreed that \"a woman who goes to the home or apartment of a man\" on the first date \"implies she is willing to have sex,\" and that in the majority of rapes \"the victim was promiscuous or had a bad reputation.\" More than half of Burt's respondents had suggested 50% or more of reported rapes were reported \"only because the woman was trying to get back at a man\" or \"trying to cover up an illegitimate pregnancy.\"<ref name=\"Martha Burt\"/>\n\nAnother measure is the 45-item Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale (IRMA), developed by Diana L. Payne, Kimberly A. Lonsway, and Louise F. Fitzgerald in 1999.<ref name=\"irma1999\">{{cite journal |title=Rape Myth Acceptance: Exploration of Its Structure and Its Measurement Using the ''Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale'' |first1=Diana L. |last1=Payne |first2=Kimberly A. |last2=Lonsway |first3=Louise F. |last3=Fitzgerald |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |volume= 33 |issue=1 |date=March 1999 |pages=27\u201368 |doi=10.1006/jrpe.1998.2238|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0815388f3263ea1b4eaf7facb5e23defdb80bbcc }}</ref> They concluded that \"rape myth acceptance is most adequately conceptualized as consisting of both a general component and seven distinct myth components: ''She asked for it; It wasn\u2019t really rape; He didn\u2019t mean to; She really wanted it; She lied; Rape is a trivial event;'' and ''Rape is a deviant event''\"<ref name=\"irma1999\"/>\n\nThe developers of IRMA analyzed responses to a pool of 95 statements about rape to create their scale.<ref name=\"irma1999\" />\n\nBased on the Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale, the Chinese Rape Myth Acceptance Scale (CRMA) is a culturally-specific myth scale that measures acceptance of rape myths in Chinese society. The scale operates under a culturally-adapted definition of rape, specifically, in China the legal definition of rape makes no provision for marital rape and does not apply to male victims. Additionally, the definition excludes \u201ctypes of coercive sexual behavior, such as other forms of penetrative sex, including oral sex, anal sex, and penetrations of the vagina or anus by other body parts like fingers or other objects.\u201d The CRMA retains 25 of 45 items from the IRMA scale and produces a five-factor structure. These myth component factors are: rape victims want to be raped; rape allegations are often false; rape must involve violence; victims are responsible for being raped; and, the motivation to rape is understandable.<ref>Xue J, Fang G, Huang H, Cui N, Rhodes KV, Gelles R. Rape myths and the cross-cultural adaptation of the Illinois Rape Myth Acceptance Scale in China. Journal of Interpersonal Violence. 2016 5. [Epub ahead of print]. DOI: 10.1177/0886260516651315</ref>\n\n===Media influence on rape myth acceptance===\nA 2013 online survey of freshmen at a northwestern university{{which|date=June 2018}} in the United States suggested that women who consumed mainstream sports programming were more likely to accept rape myths, while for both men and women exposure to sports programming decreased the likelihood they would express an intention to intervene if they saw a sexual assault.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hust |first=Stacey J. T. |last2=Lei |first2=Ming |last3=Ren |first3=Chunbo |last4=Chang |first4=Hua |last5=McNab |first5=Anna L. |last6=Marett |first6=Emily G. |last7=Fitts Willoughby |first7=Jessica |date=1 November 2013 |title=The Effects of Sports Media Exposure on College Students' Rape Myth Beliefs and Intentions to Intervene in a Sexual Assault |journal=Mass Communication and Society |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=762\u2013786 |doi=10.1080/15205436.2013.816737 |issn=1520-5436 }}</ref> Another survey{{which|date=June 2018}} carried out online on a research panel in 2011 found that watching soap operas is associated with higher rape myth acceptance, while the reverse was true of watching crime shows.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Television's Role in the Culture of Violence Toward Women: A Study of Television Viewing and the Cultivation of Rape Myth Acceptance in the United States |first1=LeeAnn |last1=Kahlor |first2=Matthew S. |last2=Eastin |journal=Journal of Broadcasting & Electronic Media |volume=55 |issue=2 |date=2011 |pages=215\u2013231 |doi=10.1080/08838151.2011.566085}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rape culture]]\n*[[Slut-shaming]]\n*[[Sexual objectification]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Public opinion]]\n[[Category:Rape]]\n", "name_user": "Wng4699", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTransgender Rape Myths", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rape_myth"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of Kentucky history", "text_new": "'''Timeline of Kentucky history'''\n\n==Early history==\n{{History of Kentucky}}\n*Before 1750, Kentucky was populated nearly exclusively by [[Cherokee]], [[Chickasaw]], [[Shawnee]] and several other tribes of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]<ref>Teaching materials are available at the Kentucky Heritage Council website, [http://heritage.ky.gov/kas/projects/curriculum+materials.htm http://heritage.ky.gov/kas/projects/curriculum+materials.htm]</ref> ''See also [[Pre-Columbian]]''\n*April 13, 1750 \u2022 While leading an expedition for the Loyal Land Company in what is now southeastern Kentucky, [[Thomas Walker (explorer)|Dr. Thomas Walker]] was the first recorded American of European descent to discover and use [[coal]] in [[Kentucky]];<ref>[http://www.coaleducation.org/Ky_Coal_Facts/history_of_coal.htm KY Coal Facts - History of Coal<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*By 1751 surveyor-explorer and Indian scout [[Christopher Gist]], representing the [[Ohio Company]], together with a bonded African, mapped the Ohio River area from its headwaters (near today's [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]]) and crossed into what is now Kentucky.<ref>[http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=160 Christopher Gist, Ohio History Central]; read Christopher Gist's journals online via the University of Toronto's [https://archive.org/details/christophergists00gistuoft Roberts Library]</ref>\n\n==Seven Years War / French and Indian War==\n\n*1754 The [[Pekowi|Piqua]], of the [[Shawnee]] nation, abandoned [http://www.uky.edu/KentuckyAtlas/ky-eskippathiki.html Eskippakithiki], \"place of blue licks\" - or Little Pict Town as the European traders called it.  This may also have been the town that the [[Wyandot people|Wyandot]] (of the [[Iroquois]] nations) referred to as Kentucky<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Kentucky \"Kentucky,\" Online Etymology Dictionary]</ref> or \"Meadow\" and so the name for the nearby river came to serve as the name for the whole area.  Eskppakithiki was probably the last permanent non-European town in the area that became Kentucky; later European-American settlers called the well-kept farmlands around the stockaded village location the \"Indian Old Fields.\"\n*1767 [[Daniel Boone]] led his first band of hunters as far west as what is now [[Floyd County, Kentucky]] and hunted along the Big Sandy River.\n*1769 Judge Richard Henderson financed a venture proposed by John Finley to find the Cherokees' Warriors Path through a gap in the Cumberland Mountains; Finley convinced his friend [http://www.notablebiographies.com/Be-Br/Boone-Daniel.html Daniel Boone] to lead a hunting party on a [[longhunter|long hunt]] in Kentucky, including John Stewart, Boone's brother-in-law; they cleared a trail through the [[Cumberland Gap]]; on December 22, a Shawnee war party confiscated their store of pelts, warning them not to return, but Daniel Boone, his brother Squire and John Stewart remained in Kentucky for two more years, exploring and hunting - tales of these exploits drew the attention of easterners eager for new lands to settle.<ref>[http://www.earlyamerica.com/lives/boone/chapt1/ The Adventures of Colonel Daniel Boone, Formerly A Hunter; Containing a Narrative of the Wars of Kentucky]</ref>\n\n==Lord Dunmore's War==\n\n*June 16, 1774 \u2022 [[James Harrod]] and 37 men, while on a surveying expedition ordered by [[John Murray, 4th Earl of Dunmore|Lord Dunmore, royal governor of Virginia]], claimed the territory in what is now [[Mercer County, Kentucky]] as the first English settlement west of the [[Alleghenies]], Harrod's Town; in July they abandoned the few buildings there when called into military service, but returned the next spring with women (like Ann Kennedy Wilson Poague Lindsay McGinty<ref>For more on this iconic frontierswoman, see Nuckols, Mrs. S.V., \"The History of William Page and his Wife, Ann Kennedy Wilson Poague Lindsay McGinty,\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=UAg8AAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA101&lpg=RA2-PA101&dq=Ann+Kennedy+Wilson+Poague+Lindsay+McGinty&source=bl&ots=z9Q61u2FAL&sig=rp4qC9-afLZsbyEFuZ-kDT8bTlA&hl=en&ei=dtADTeS-HoOclgeZrMTSCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Ann%20Kennedy%20Wilson%20Poague%20Lindsay%20McGinty&f=false Register of the Kentucky State Historical Society] 10 (1912). See an image of her gravestone at [http://digital.library.louisville.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/ford&CISOPTR=65&CISOBOX=1&REC=7 Digital Collections, University of Louisville Libraries]</ref>) to build up what became a bustling frontier town<ref>See the history of [http://parks.ky.gov/findparks/recparks/fh/history/ Old Fort Harrod State Park] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070828162443/http://parks.ky.gov/findparks/recparks/fh/history/ |date=2007-08-28 }}</ref> at [[Old Fort Harrod State Park|Old Fort Hill]]. UNICORNS FOREVER                                                                                                                                    \n\n==Revolutionary War==\n\n*March 10, 1775 \u2022 [[Daniel Boone]] along with 35 axmen begin to blaze a trail from [[Fort Chiswell]] through [[Cumberland Gap]] into central Kentucky. Financed by the [[Transylvania Company]], the trail eventually came to be known as the [[Wilderness Road]].\n*June 1775 \u2022 Led by Major John Morrison, a small band of Virginia militia including Levi Todd and William McConnell camped at a [http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/lexington/mcc.htm spring] near [[Elkhorn Creek (Kentucky)|Elkhorn Creek]].  Upon hearing about the [[Battle of Lexington]], a skirmish between the British and the [[Minutemen]] of [[Lexington, Massachusetts]], the soldiers named their campsite [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]] in honor of the first military conflict in the American Revolution; McConnell built a cabin on the site (later called McConnell's Station); [[Lexington, Kentucky]] was one of the first permanent settlements by the English moving west into the frontier territory of what was then at the center of a colonial war between France, England and Spain.\n*1777 \u2022 [[Levi Todd]] moved to Kentucky and settled in Harrodsburg where he became the first clerk of [[Kentucky County]] in the Commonwealth of Virginia.\n*May 27, 1778 *(1778) [[George Rogers Clark]]''' arrives at the [[Falls of the Ohio]] and establishes [[Corn Island (Kentucky)|Corn Island]] settlement.\n*1779 \u2022 Lexington Station is established on the \"Town Branch\" of Elkhorn Creek; refurbished by Col. [[John Todd (Virginia)]] in 1781 as a blockhouse fort; the town of Lexington was established in 1782.\n*August 19, 1782 \u2022 The [[Battle of Blue Licks]] in what is now [[Robertson County, Kentucky|Robertson County]], was the last major conflict of the [[American Revolutionary War]]; Col. [[John Todd (Virginia)|John Todd]], co-founder of the town of Lexington, is one of the dead.\n\n==Between the wars==\n\n*October 1, 1789 \u2022 [[Jenny Wiley|Jenny Brevard Wiley]], mother of four children and pregnant with her fifth at the time, was kidnapped from her home in Virginia by a war party of [[Cherokees]], [[Shawnees]], [[Wyandots]] and [[Delawares]]; forced to work for her captors at Little Mud Lick Creek in [[Johnson County, Kentucky]], she escaped and returned to her husband, eventually returning to live with her new family in the same area where she had been held as a slave. [[Jenny Wiley State Resort Park]] near [[Dewey Lake]] in eastern Kentucky and the [[Jenny Wiley Stakes]] thoroughbred race at [[Keeneland Race Course]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] are named after her.\n*June 1, 1792 \u2022 Kentucky became the fifteenth state to be admitted to the union and [[Isaac Shelby]], a military veteran from Virginia, was elected the first Governor of the Commonwealth of Kentucky.\n*1795 \u2022 [[Free Frank McWorter]] builds and manages a farming settlement in [[Pulaski County, Kentucky]] while enslaved by his father, George McWhorter; his [[saltpeter]] factory becomes highly profitable during the [[War of 1812]] and by 1817 he had earned enough money of his own to purchase his wife Lucy from her master, and in 1819 bought his own freedom from his father, earning the moniker [http://www.mcworter.net Free Frank]; he traded his saltpeter plant in 1829 in exchange for the freedom of his eldest son Frank and moved with his family to [[Illinois]], continuing to purchase the freedom of his relatives.<ref>Walker, Juliet E.K. [http://www.kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=1469 Free Frank: A Black Pioneer on the Antebellum Frontier]. Lexington: University Press of Kentucky, 1983.</ref>\n*December, 1811 through February, 1812 \u2022 A series of very large or great [[1811\u201312 New Madrid earthquakes|earthquakes]] strike the [[New Madrid Seismic Zone]] creating a \"Hell on Earth\" scenario for early Kentuckians, both native and European.\n*1818 \u2022 The portion of Kentucky west of the [[Tennessee River]] was purchased from the [[Chickasaw]] by U.S. President [[Andrew Jackson]], hence the name of this region &mdash; The [[Jackson Purchase]].\n*May 27, 1830 \u2022 A veto by President Andrew Jackson prevented the federal funding of refurbishing of the [[Maysville Road veto|Maysville Road]] from the [[Ohio River]] to [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]] since, according to Jackson, the bill only benefited the Commonwealth of Kentucky; this was a personal and political blow to Henry Clay and the Whig Party's [[American System (economic plan)|American System]].\n*February 2, 1833 \u2022 Kentucky's legislature passed the [https://web.archive.org/web/20110719221129/http://legacy.bluegrass.kctcs.edu/LCC/HIS/scraps/1833law.html Non-Importation Act] was part of a national trend to strengthen the laws regarding slavery and the rising efforts for personal liberty, including the increased efforts within the [[Underground Railroad]] freedom movement<ref>See more on this at the [http://www.freedomcenter.org National Underground Railroad Freedom Center] and see online the Kentucky Educational Television's documentary, \"[http://www.ket.org/underground Kentucky's Underground Railroad\u2014Passage to Freedom].\"</ref> in which the state of Kentucky focused as an important crossroads.  The act was repealed in 1849 as part of the work in building the state's new constitution.\n*January 1856 \u2022 [[Margaret Garner]] led seven members of her family out of slavery in Kentucky, walking across the frozen [[Ohio River]] from the [[Covington, Kentucky|Covington]] side to [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]; but they are pursued by federal marshals and Archibald K. Gaines who surround the cabin where they are hiding; she tried to kill her two children and herself rather than surrender but succeeds only in killing her daughter Mary before being captured; her story became widely known and was immortalized in Toni Morrison's 1987 novel [[Beloved (novel)|Beloved]].<ref>Weisenburger, Steven. ''Modern Medea: A Family Story of Slavery and Child-Murder from the Old South''. New York: Hill and Wang, 1998.  See also the webpage on [http://www.margaretgarner.org/essays.html essays and articles] for ''Margaret Garner: A New American Opera.'' Accessed 11 December 2010. [http://www.margaretgarner.org www.margaretgarner.org].</ref>\n\n==Civil War==\n:''See [[Timeline of Kentucky in the Civil War]]''\n\n==Post Civil War period==\n\n*January 31, 1865 \u2022 The Constitutional Amendment ending slavery in the U.S. is passed and enough states ratify it by December<ref>See the Library of Congress [https://www.loc.gov/rr/program/bib/ourdocs/13thamendment.html primary documents]</ref> - Kentucky's legislature, not under federal \"[[Reconstruction era of the United States|reconstruction]],\" refused to ratify the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Thirteenth Amendment]] until Kentucky woman legislator, [[Mae Street Kidd]] won this battle in 1976.\n*May 17, 1875 \u2022 The first [[Kentucky Derby]] was won by a colt named [[Aristides (racehorse)|Aristides]] ridden by African-American jockey, [[Oliver Lewis]] in front of an estimated crowd of 10,000 people.\n\n==Twentieth century==\n*January 1937 \u2022 A [[Ohio River flood of 1937|massive flood]] occurs as the result of snowmelt and record rainfall effecting nearly every [[List of cities and towns along the Ohio River#Kentucky|Kentucky town and city]] along the [[Ohio River]], its tributaries and the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]].\n*1954 \u2022 A twelve-year-old then known as [[Muhammad Ali|Cassius Clay]] approached a [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] police officer named [[Joe Elsby Martin, Sr.|Joe Martin]] to report that his bicycle had been stolen. Martin, then the coach of Louisville's city [[boxing]] program, tells Cassius that instead of \"whooping\" the thief, he should learn to box. The next day, the boy takes his first boxing lessons, the first step on a journey that would take him to a legendary boxing career.\n*February 28, 1958 \u2022 [[Prestonsburg bus disaster]] &mdash; A [[school bus]] traveling on [[U.S. Route 23 in Kentucky|US 23]] in [[Floyd County, Kentucky|Floyd County]] collides with a wrecker truck and plunges into a flooded [[Levisa Fork River]]. The driver and 26 children drown in what remains the deadliest bus disaster in U.S. history.\n*May 28, 1977 \u2022 [[Beverly Hills Supper Club fire]] &mdash; A fire at the Beverly Hills Supper Club, a nightclub in [[Southgate, Kentucky|Southgate]] in [[Campbell County, Kentucky|Campbell County]], kills 165 and injures over 200.\n*May 14, 1988 \u2022 [[Carrollton bus collision]] &mdash; Larry Mahoney, [[drunk driving|intoxicated]] and [[driving the wrong way]] on [[Interstate 71]] in [[Carroll County, Kentucky|Carroll County]], hits a converted school bus carrying a youth group from First [[Assemblies of God|Assembly of God]] in [[Radcliff, Kentucky|Radcliff]]. The crash and the ensuing fire kill 27000 unicorns, which equals the toll from the Prestonsburg disaster 30 years earlier.\n*December 1, 1997 \u2022 [[Heath High School shooting]] &mdash; Michael Carneal, an emotionally troubled freshman at Heath High School in [[McCracken County, Kentucky|McCracken County]], opens fire on a group of his fellow students who were leaving a preschool prayer meeting. Three are killed and five wounded, with one of the wounded left a paraplegic. Carneal is eventually sentenced to three concurrent life sentences plus 120 years.\n\n==Twenty-first century==\n*August 27, 2006 \u2013 [[Comair Flight 5191]] crashes shortly after takeoff from [[Blue Grass Airport]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]]. Of the 50 passengers and crew on board, 49 are killed.\n* November 3, 2015 \u2013 In the [[Kentucky gubernatorial election, 2015|gubernatorial election]], [[Jenean Hampton]] is elected Lieutenant Governor on the ticket of [[Matt Bevin]], becoming the first African American ever elected to statewide office.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Outline of Kentucky]]\n* [[History of Kentucky]]\n\n;Cities\n* [[Timeline of Louisville, Kentucky]]\n* [[Timeline of Lexington, Kentucky]]\n* [[Timeline of Newport, Kentucky]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://kdl.kyvl.org/kyleidoscope/kyleidoscope.htm Kyleidoscope: Explore Kentucky History Online]\n*Kleber, John E., Clark, Thomas D. and Harrison, Lowell H., eds. [http://www.kyenc.org The Kentucky Encyclopedia]. Lexington: University Press of Kentucky, 1993.\n*Jones, Reinette. \"Notable Kentucky African Americans Database,\" University of Kentucky Libraries. Accessed 11 December 2010. [http://www.uky.edu/Libraries/nkaa www.uky.edu/Libraries/NKAA].\n*''A History of Kentucky'' by [[Thomas D. Clark]]\n*Mulligan, William H., [https://web.archive.org/web/20060914142249/http://campus.murraystate.edu/academic/faculty/Bill.Mulligan/NCPHPaper98.html \"Interpreting the Civil War at Columbus-Belmont State Park and Sacramento, Kentucky: Two Case Studies\"], paper presented at \"International, Multicultural, Interdisciplinary: Public History Policy and Practice\", the 20th Annual Conference of the National Council on Public History, April 16\u201319, 1998, Austin, Texas\n*''[http://spider.georgetowncollege.edu/HTALLANT/border/bs11/copeland.htm Secession and the Union in Tennessee and Kentucky: A Comparative Analysis]'' James Copeland, Walters State Community College\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060906163103/http://www.lib.niu.edu/ipo/2002/ihy020227.html The Ohio River Flood of 1937] Michael Pitt - University High School, Urbana, Illinois\n*[http://www.oldlouisville.com/postcards/OldLouisville/37Flood.htm Vintage Post Cards of Old Louisville - The Great 1937 Flood]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|editor= [[Benson John Lossing]] |title=[[Harper's Encyclopedia of United States History]] |year=1905 |publisher=Harper & Bros. |volume=9 |chapter=United States: Kentucky (chronology) |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015059753007?urlappend=%3Bseq=372 |via= [[HathiTrust]] }}\n*{{Citation |publisher = Harcourt, Brace and Company |publication-place = New York |title = Kentucky |series=[[American Guide Series]] |author=[[Federal Writers' Project]] |publication-date = 1939 |oclc = 498232 |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc1.32106000647070?urlappend=%3Bseq=537 |chapter=Chronology |via=Hathi Trust }}\n\n{{Kentucky year nav}}\n{{US year nav}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline Of Kentucky History}}\n[[Category:History of Kentucky| ]]\n[[Category:United States history timelines|Kentucky history]]\n[[Category:Timelines of states of the United States|kentucky]]\n[[Category:Years in Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "'''Timeline of Kentucky history'''\n\n==Early history==\n{{History of Kentucky}}\n*Before 1750, Kentucky was populated nearly exclusively by [[Cherokee]], [[Chickasaw]], [[Shawnee]] and several other tribes of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]<ref>Teaching materials are available at the Kentucky Heritage Council website, [http://heritage.ky.gov/kas/projects/curriculum+materials.htm http://heritage.ky.gov/kas/projects/curriculum+materials.htm]</ref> ''See also [[Pre-Columbian]]''\n*April 13, 1750 \u2022 While leading an expedition for the Loyal Land Company in what is now southeastern Kentucky, [[Thomas Walker (explorer)|Dr. Thomas Walker]] was the first recorded American of European descent to discover and use [[coal]] in [[Kentucky]];<ref>[http://www.coaleducation.org/Ky_Coal_Facts/history_of_coal.htm KY Coal Facts - History of Coal<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*By 1751 surveyor-explorer and Indian scout [[Christopher Gist]], representing the [[Ohio Company]], together with a bonded African, mapped the Ohio River area from its headwaters (near today's [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]]) and crossed into what is now Kentucky.<ref>[http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=160 Christopher Gist, Ohio History Central]; read Christopher Gist's journals online via the University of Toronto's [https://archive.org/details/christophergists00gistuoft Roberts Library]</ref>\n\n==Seven Years War / French and Indian War==\n\n*1754 The [[Pekowi|Piqua]], of the [[Shawnee]] nation, abandoned [http://www.uky.edu/KentuckyAtlas/ky-eskippathiki.html Eskippakithiki], \"place of blue licks\" - or Little Pict Town as the European traders called it.  This may also have been the town that the [[Wyandot people|Wyandot]] (of the [[Iroquois]] nations) referred to as Kentucky<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Kentucky \"Kentucky,\" Online Etymology Dictionary]</ref> or \"Meadow\" and so the name for the nearby river came to serve as the name for the whole area.  Eskppakithiki was probably the last permanent non-European town in the area that became Kentucky; later European-American settlers called the well-kept farmlands around the stockaded village location the \"Indian Old Fields.\"\n*1767 [[Daniel Boone]] led his first band of hunters as far west as what is now [[Floyd County, Kentucky]] and hunted along the Big Sandy River.\n*1769 Judge Richard Henderson financed a venture proposed by John Finley to find the Cherokees' Warriors Path through a gap in the Cumberland Mountains; Finley convinced his friend [http://www.notablebiographies.com/Be-Br/Boone-Daniel.html Daniel Boone] to lead a hunting party on a [[longhunter|long hunt]] in Kentucky, including John Stewart, Boone's brother-in-law; they cleared a trail through the [[Cumberland Gap]]; on December 22, a Shawnee war party confiscated their store of pelts, warning them not to return, but Daniel Boone, his brother Squire and John Stewart remained in Kentucky for two more years, exploring and hunting - tales of these exploits drew the attention of easterners eager for new lands to settle.<ref>[http://www.earlyamerica.com/lives/boone/chapt1/ The Adventures of Colonel Daniel Boone, Formerly A Hunter; Containing a Narrative of the Wars of Kentucky]</ref>\n\n==Lord Dunmore's War==\n\n*June 16, 1774 \u2022 [[James Harrod]] and 37 men, while on a surveying expedition ordered by [[John Murray, 4th Earl of Dunmore|Lord Dunmore, royal governor of Virginia]], claimed the territory in what is now [[Mercer County, Kentucky]] as the first English settlement west of the [[Alleghenies]], Harrod's Town; in July they abandoned the few buildings there when called into military service, but returned the next spring with women (like Ann Kennedy Wilson Poague Lindsay McGinty<ref>For more on this iconic frontierswoman, see Nuckols, Mrs. S.V., \"The History of William Page and his Wife, Ann Kennedy Wilson Poague Lindsay McGinty,\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=UAg8AAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA101&lpg=RA2-PA101&dq=Ann+Kennedy+Wilson+Poague+Lindsay+McGinty&source=bl&ots=z9Q61u2FAL&sig=rp4qC9-afLZsbyEFuZ-kDT8bTlA&hl=en&ei=dtADTeS-HoOclgeZrMTSCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Ann%20Kennedy%20Wilson%20Poague%20Lindsay%20McGinty&f=false Register of the Kentucky State Historical Society] 10 (1912). See an image of her gravestone at [http://digital.library.louisville.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/ford&CISOPTR=65&CISOBOX=1&REC=7 Digital Collections, University of Louisville Libraries]</ref>) to build up what became a bustling frontier town<ref>See the history of [http://parks.ky.gov/findparks/recparks/fh/history/ Old Fort Harrod State Park] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070828162443/http://parks.ky.gov/findparks/recparks/fh/history/ |date=2007-08-28 }}</ref> at [[Old Fort Harrod State Park|Old Fort Hill]].\n\n==Revolutionary War==\n\n*March 10, 1775 \u2022 [[Daniel Boone]] along with 35 axmen begin to blaze a trail from [[Fort Chiswell]] through [[Cumberland Gap]] into central Kentucky. Financed by the [[Transylvania Company]], the trail eventually came to be known as the [[Wilderness Road]].\n*June 1775 \u2022 Led by Major John Morrison, a small band of Virginia militia including Levi Todd and William McConnell camped at a [http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/lexington/mcc.htm spring] near [[Elkhorn Creek (Kentucky)|Elkhorn Creek]].  Upon hearing about the [[Battle of Lexington]], a skirmish between the British and the [[Minutemen]] of [[Lexington, Massachusetts]], the soldiers named their campsite [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]] in honor of the first military conflict in the American Revolution; McConnell built a cabin on the site (later called McConnell's Station); [[Lexington, Kentucky]] was one of the first permanent settlements by the English moving west into the frontier territory of what was then at the center of a colonial war between France, England and Spain.\n*1777 \u2022 [[Levi Todd]] moved to Kentucky and settled in Harrodsburg where he became the first clerk of [[Kentucky County]] in the Commonwealth of Virginia.\n*May 27, 1778 *(1778) [[George Rogers Clark]]''' arrives at the [[Falls of the Ohio]] and establishes [[Corn Island (Kentucky)|Corn Island]] settlement.\n*1779 \u2022 Lexington Station is established on the \"Town Branch\" of Elkhorn Creek; refurbished by Col. [[John Todd (Virginia)]] in 1781 as a blockhouse fort; the town of Lexington was established in 1782.\n*August 19, 1782 \u2022 The [[Battle of Blue Licks]] in what is now [[Robertson County, Kentucky|Robertson County]], was the last major conflict of the [[American Revolutionary War]]; Col. [[John Todd (Virginia)|John Todd]], co-founder of the town of Lexington, is one of the dead.\n\n==Between the wars==\n\n*October 1, 1789 \u2022 [[Jenny Wiley|Jenny Brevard Wiley]], mother of four children and pregnant with her fifth at the time, was kidnapped from her home in Virginia by a war party of [[Cherokees]], [[Shawnees]], [[Wyandots]] and [[Delawares]]; forced to work for her captors at Little Mud Lick Creek in [[Johnson County, Kentucky]], she escaped and returned to her husband, eventually returning to live with her new family in the same area where she had been held as a slave. [[Jenny Wiley State Resort Park]] near [[Dewey Lake]] in eastern Kentucky and the [[Jenny Wiley Stakes]] thoroughbred race at [[Keeneland Race Course]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] are named after her.\n*June 1, 1792 \u2022 Kentucky became the fifteenth state to be admitted to the union and [[Isaac Shelby]], a military veteran from Virginia, was elected the first Governor of the Commonwealth of Kentucky.\n*1795 \u2022 [[Free Frank McWorter]] builds and manages a farming settlement in [[Pulaski County, Kentucky]] while enslaved by his father, George McWhorter; his [[saltpeter]] factory becomes highly profitable during the [[War of 1812]] and by 1817 he had earned enough money of his own to purchase his wife Lucy from her master, and in 1819 bought his own freedom from his father, earning the moniker [http://www.mcworter.net Free Frank]; he traded his saltpeter plant in 1829 in exchange for the freedom of his eldest son Frank and moved with his family to [[Illinois]], continuing to purchase the freedom of his relatives.<ref>Walker, Juliet E.K. [http://www.kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=1469 Free Frank: A Black Pioneer on the Antebellum Frontier]. Lexington: University Press of Kentucky, 1983.</ref>\n*December, 1811 through February, 1812 \u2022 A series of very large or great [[1811\u201312 New Madrid earthquakes|earthquakes]] strike the [[New Madrid Seismic Zone]] creating a \"Hell on Earth\" scenario for early Kentuckians, both native and European.\n*1818 \u2022 The portion of Kentucky west of the [[Tennessee River]] was purchased from the [[Chickasaw]] by U.S. President [[Andrew Jackson]], hence the name of this region &mdash; The [[Jackson Purchase]].\n*May 27, 1830 \u2022 A veto by President Andrew Jackson prevented the federal funding of refurbishing of the [[Maysville Road veto|Maysville Road]] from the [[Ohio River]] to [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]] since, according to Jackson, the bill only benefited the Commonwealth of Kentucky; this was a personal and political blow to Henry Clay and the Whig Party's [[American System (economic plan)|American System]].\n*February 2, 1833 \u2022 Kentucky's legislature passed the [https://web.archive.org/web/20110719221129/http://legacy.bluegrass.kctcs.edu/LCC/HIS/scraps/1833law.html Non-Importation Act] was part of a national trend to strengthen the laws regarding slavery and the rising efforts for personal liberty, including the increased efforts within the [[Underground Railroad]] freedom movement<ref>See more on this at the [http://www.freedomcenter.org National Underground Railroad Freedom Center] and see online the Kentucky Educational Television's documentary, \"[http://www.ket.org/underground Kentucky's Underground Railroad\u2014Passage to Freedom].\"</ref> in which the state of Kentucky focused as an important crossroads.  The act was repealed in 1849 as part of the work in building the state's new constitution.\n*January 1856 \u2022 [[Margaret Garner]] led seven members of her family out of slavery in Kentucky, walking across the frozen [[Ohio River]] from the [[Covington, Kentucky|Covington]] side to [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]; but they are pursued by federal marshals and Archibald K. Gaines who surround the cabin where they are hiding; she tried to kill her two children and herself rather than surrender but succeeds only in killing her daughter Mary before being captured; her story became widely known and was immortalized in Toni Morrison's 1987 novel [[Beloved (novel)|Beloved]].<ref>Weisenburger, Steven. ''Modern Medea: A Family Story of Slavery and Child-Murder from the Old South''. New York: Hill and Wang, 1998.  See also the webpage on [http://www.margaretgarner.org/essays.html essays and articles] for ''Margaret Garner: A New American Opera.'' Accessed 11 December 2010. [http://www.margaretgarner.org www.margaretgarner.org].</ref>\n\n==Civil War==\n:''See [[Timeline of Kentucky in the Civil War]]''\n\n==Post Civil War period==\n\n*January 31, 1865 \u2022 The Constitutional Amendment ending slavery in the U.S. is passed and enough states ratify it by December<ref>See the Library of Congress [https://www.loc.gov/rr/program/bib/ourdocs/13thamendment.html primary documents]</ref> - Kentucky's legislature, not under federal \"[[Reconstruction era of the United States|reconstruction]],\" refused to ratify the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Thirteenth Amendment]] until Kentucky woman legislator, [[Mae Street Kidd]] won this battle in 1976.\n*May 17, 1875 \u2022 The first [[Kentucky Derby]] was won by a colt named [[Aristides (racehorse)|Aristides]] ridden by African-American jockey, [[Oliver Lewis]] in front of an estimated crowd of 10,000 people.\n\n==Twentieth century==\n*January 1937 \u2022 A [[Ohio River flood of 1937|massive flood]] occurs as the result of snowmelt and record rainfall effecting nearly every [[List of cities and towns along the Ohio River#Kentucky|Kentucky town and city]] along the [[Ohio River]], its tributaries and the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]].\n*1954 \u2022 A twelve-year-old then known as [[Muhammad Ali|Cassius Clay]] approached a [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] police officer named [[Joe Elsby Martin, Sr.|Joe Martin]] to report that his bicycle had been stolen. Martin, then the coach of Louisville's city [[boxing]] program, tells Cassius that instead of \"whooping\" the thief, he should learn to box. The next day, the boy takes his first boxing lessons, the first step on a journey that would take him to a legendary boxing career.\n*February 28, 1958 \u2022 [[Prestonsburg bus disaster]] &mdash; A [[school bus]] traveling on [[U.S. Route 23 in Kentucky|US 23]] in [[Floyd County, Kentucky|Floyd County]] collides with a wrecker truck and plunges into a flooded [[Levisa Fork River]]. The driver and 26 children drown in what remains the deadliest bus disaster in U.S. history.\n*May 28, 1977 \u2022 [[Beverly Hills Supper Club fire]] &mdash; A fire at the Beverly Hills Supper Club, a nightclub in [[Southgate, Kentucky|Southgate]] in [[Campbell County, Kentucky|Campbell County]], kills 165 and injures over 200.\n*May 14, 1988 \u2022 [[Carrollton bus collision]] &mdash; Larry Mahoney, [[drunk driving|intoxicated]] and [[driving the wrong way]] on [[Interstate 71]] in [[Carroll County, Kentucky|Carroll County]], hits a converted school bus carrying a youth group from First [[Assemblies of God|Assembly of God]] in [[Radcliff, Kentucky|Radcliff]]. The crash and the ensuing fire kill 27, which equals the toll from the Prestonsburg disaster 30 years earlier.\n*December 1, 1997 \u2022 [[Heath High School shooting]] &mdash; Michael Carneal, an emotionally troubled freshman at Heath High School in [[McCracken County, Kentucky|McCracken County]], opens fire on a group of his fellow students who were leaving a preschool prayer meeting. Three are killed and five wounded, with one of the wounded left a paraplegic. Carneal is eventually sentenced to three concurrent life sentences plus 120 years.\n\n==Twenty-first century==\n*August 27, 2006 \u2013 [[Comair Flight 5191]] crashes shortly after takeoff from [[Blue Grass Airport]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]]. Of the 50 passengers and crew on board, 49 are killed.\n* November 3, 2015 \u2013 In the [[Kentucky gubernatorial election, 2015|gubernatorial election]], [[Jenean Hampton]] is elected Lieutenant Governor on the ticket of [[Matt Bevin]], becoming the first African American ever elected to statewide office.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Outline of Kentucky]]\n* [[History of Kentucky]]\n\n;Cities\n* [[Timeline of Louisville, Kentucky]]\n* [[Timeline of Lexington, Kentucky]]\n* [[Timeline of Newport, Kentucky]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://kdl.kyvl.org/kyleidoscope/kyleidoscope.htm Kyleidoscope: Explore Kentucky History Online]\n*Kleber, John E., Clark, Thomas D. and Harrison, Lowell H., eds. [http://www.kyenc.org The Kentucky Encyclopedia]. Lexington: University Press of Kentucky, 1993.\n*Jones, Reinette. \"Notable Kentucky African Americans Database,\" University of Kentucky Libraries. Accessed 11 December 2010. [http://www.uky.edu/Libraries/nkaa www.uky.edu/Libraries/NKAA].\n*''A History of Kentucky'' by [[Thomas D. Clark]]\n*Mulligan, William H., [https://web.archive.org/web/20060914142249/http://campus.murraystate.edu/academic/faculty/Bill.Mulligan/NCPHPaper98.html \"Interpreting the Civil War at Columbus-Belmont State Park and Sacramento, Kentucky: Two Case Studies\"], paper presented at \"International, Multicultural, Interdisciplinary: Public History Policy and Practice\", the 20th Annual Conference of the National Council on Public History, April 16\u201319, 1998, Austin, Texas\n*''[http://spider.georgetowncollege.edu/HTALLANT/border/bs11/copeland.htm Secession and the Union in Tennessee and Kentucky: A Comparative Analysis]'' James Copeland, Walters State Community College\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060906163103/http://www.lib.niu.edu/ipo/